  "e62961a0": {
    "title": "Absence Seizure Anticonvulsants",
    "primaryType": "concept",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Epilepsy",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Anticonvulsants"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Absence seizure anticonvulsants</b> are medications specifically effective in treating [[a0c128f4|absence seizures]], primarily by targeting the T-type calcium channels in thalamic neurons, which are implicated in the generation of the characteristic <mark>3 Hz spike-and-wave</mark> discharges.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>First-Line Agent:</b> [[a90f6fb4|Ethosuximide]] is the <u>first-line</u> and most specific drug for treating isolated absence seizures.</li><li><b>Mechanism of Ethosuximide:</b> Blocks T-type Ca<sup>2+</sup> channels in thalamic neurons, disrupting the oscillatory rhythm between the thalamus and cortex that generates absence seizures.</li><li><b>Alternative Agent:</b> [[valproic_acid|Valproic acid]] is also effective and is preferred if the patient has concomitant generalized tonic-clonic seizures. It works by blocking T-type Ca<sup>2+</sup> channels and increasing [[5aa5cb91|GABA]] levels.</li><li><b>Contraindicated Agents:</b> Certain anticonvulsants, such as [[eddd2bc5|carbamazepine]] and [[5aea213f|phenytoin]], can <u>worsen</u> absence seizures.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> For a child with staring spells and a 3 Hz spike-and-wave EEG, the answer for treatment is almost always [[a90f6fb4|Ethosuximide]]. If tonic-clonic seizures are also mentioned, consider [[valproic_acid|Valproic acid]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The treatment of [[a0c128f4|absence seizures]] is highly specific, with [[a90f6fb4|Ethosuximide]] being the drug of choice due to its targeted blockade of thalamic T-type calcium channels, while other common anticonvulsants like carbamazepine are paradoxically contraindicated.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
