  "87d19a70": {
    "title": "Achilles Reflex",
    "primaryType": "physiology",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Physical Exam",
      "Physiology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Spinal Cord"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Achilles reflex</b>, also known as the ankle jerk reflex, is a deep tendon reflex that involves plantar flexion of the foot in response to tapping the Achilles tendon, testing the integrity of the <mark>S1 and S2</mark> spinal nerve roots.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Nerve Roots:</b> Primarily tests the <b>S1</b> nerve root, with contribution from S2. Mnemonic: S<b>1</b>, 2, buckle my shoe.</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> Tapping the tendon stretches the gastrocnemius muscle, activating stretch receptors. The afferent signal travels via the tibial nerve to the S1/S2 spinal cord segments, synapses, and an efferent motor signal returns via the tibial nerve to cause plantar flexion.</li><li><b>Diminished/Absent Reflex:</b> Suggests a lower motor neuron lesion, such as a herniated disc compressing the S1 root, or peripheral neuropathy.</li><li><b>Exaggerated Reflex (Hyperreflexia):</b> Suggests an upper motor neuron lesion, such as a stroke or spinal cord injury above the S1/S2 level.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> An absent Achilles reflex is a classic finding in [[71daebd6|Tabes Dorsalis]] and [[lumbosacral_radiculopathy|S1 radiculopathy]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Achilles reflex</b> is a simple yet powerful clinical tool that specifically assesses the integrity of the S1 spinal nerve root; its absence or exaggeration can help differentiate between lower and upper motor neuron pathologies.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Tap Achilles Tendon] --> B(Stretch Gastrocnemius); B --> C(Afferent Signal via Tibial N.); C --> D[S1/S2 Spinal Cord]; D --> E(Efferent Signal via Tibial N.); E --> F(Plantar Flexion);"
    },
    "connections": [
