  "d268ace0": {
    "title": "Opioid-Induced Acute Pulmonary Edema",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Toxicology",
      "Pulmonology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Respiratory",
      "Pathology",
      "Acute Respiratory Distress Syndrome"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Opioid-induced acute pulmonary edema</b> is a form of <i>non-cardiogenic pulmonary edema</i> that can occur as a life-threatening complication of opioid overdose, characterized by increased pulmonary vascular permeability and subsequent alveolar flooding.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> The exact mechanism is multifactorial but is thought to involve direct toxic effects on the pulmonary capillary endothelium, hypoxia-induced vascular injury, and a massive sympathetic surge following transient hypoxia, all leading to <mark>increased vascular permeability</mark>.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Occurs shortly after an opioid overdose. Patients present with severe dyspnea, hypoxia, frothy pink sputum, and diffuse crackles on auscultation, often after being resuscitated with [[naloxone]].</li><li><b>Radiology:</b> Chest X-ray shows bilateral diffuse alveolar infiltrates, consistent with pulmonary edema, but with a normal cardiac silhouette (distinguishing it from cardiogenic pulmonary edema).</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> Management is supportive and includes supplemental oxygen, non-invasive or mechanical ventilation, and addressing the underlying opioid overdose. Diuretics are <u>not effective</u> as the cause is permeability, not fluid overload.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Be aware of the patient who is treated for an opioid overdose with [[naloxone]] and subsequently develops severe respiratory distress; this points towards non-cardiogenic pulmonary edema rather than a cardiac cause.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>Unlike cardiogenic pulmonary edema which is caused by high hydrostatic pressure, <b>opioid-induced pulmonary edema</b> is a permeability problem where opioid toxicity and hypoxia damage the alveolar-capillary barrier, leading to leaky vessels and flooded lungs that do not respond to diuretics.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Opioid Overdose] --> B(Hypoxia & Direct Toxicity); B --> C[Pulmonary Capillary Endothelial Damage]; C --> D[Increased Vascular Permeability]; D --> E[Alveolar Flooding]; E --> F[Non-Cardiogenic Pulmonary Edema];"
    },
    "connections": [
