    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Adenovirus</b> is a non-enveloped, double-stranded DNA virus that is a common cause of various infections, including pharyngitis, pneumonia, hemorrhagic cystitis, and notably, <i>viral conjunctivitis</i> (pink eye).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Structure:</b> Non-enveloped, icosahedral capsid with a linear dsDNA genome.</li><li><b>Transmission:</b> Transmitted via respiratory droplets, fecal-oral route, and direct contact with contaminated surfaces (fomites). Highly stable in the environment.</li><li><b>Ocular Manifestation:</b> The most common cause of viral [[c4d08c09|conjunctivitis]], presenting with a <mark>watery discharge</mark>, red eye, and often a swollen preauricular lymph node.</li><li><b>Other Clinical Syndromes:</b> Causes febrile pharyngitis, acute hemorrhagic cystitis, and pneumonia (especially in military recruits).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> In a question describing a patient (often a child) with red, watery eyes and a recent history of a cold or attending daycare, Adenovirus is the most likely pathogen. The watery discharge is key to differentiating it from bacterial conjunctivitis.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Adenovirus</b> is a highly resilient DNA virus responsible for the majority of viral conjunctivitis cases, characterized by a watery discharge that distinguishes it from the purulent discharge of bacterial causes.</p>",
