    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Age-related Macular Degeneration (AMD)</b> is a progressive neurodegenerative disease of the macula, the central part of the retina, leading to the gradual loss of <i>central vision</i>. It is the leading cause of irreversible blindness in older adults in developed countries.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Dry (Atrophic) AMD:</b> More common (~80%). Characterized by the slow breakdown of photoreceptors in the macula and the deposition of yellowish extracellular material called <mark>drusen</mark> between Bruch's membrane and the retinal pigment epithelium. Causes gradual vision loss.</li><li><b>Wet (Exudative) AMD:</b> Less common but more severe. Characterized by rapid vision loss due to choroidal neovascularization. Abnormal blood vessels grow under the retina, leak fluid and blood, and can cause scarring.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Patients report painless, progressive loss of central vision, leading to scotomas (blind spots). A key early symptom of wet AMD is <mark>metamorphopsia</mark> (straight lines appear wavy).</li><li><b>Diagnosis:</b> Fundoscopy reveals drusen (dry AMD) or hemorrhage/exudates (wet AMD). An Amsler grid is used to detect metamorphopsia.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the key difference: <b>Dry AMD = Drusen</b> and gradual loss. <b>Wet AMD = Neovascularization</b> and rapid loss. Central vision loss is the hallmark for both.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Age-related Macular Degeneration</b> specifically targets central, high-acuity vision by damaging the macula. The distinction between the slow, drusen-associated 'dry' form and the rapid, neovascular 'wet' form is critical for prognosis and management.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Aging & Genetic Factors] --> B{Macular Damage}; B --> C[Dry AMD]; C --> D[Drusen Deposition & Atrophy]; D --> E[Gradual Central Vision Loss]; B --> F[Wet AMD]; F --> G[Choroidal Neovascularization]; G --> H[Hemorrhage & Exudate]; H --> I[Rapid Central Vision Loss];"
    },
    "connections": [
