  "13d6bca7": {
    "title": "Agraphia",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Cognitive Deficit",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Brain Lesions"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Agraphia</b> is an acquired neurological disorder characterized by the <i>loss of the ability to communicate through writing</i>, stemming from damage to specific brain areas involved in language processing and motor control of the hand.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Localization:</b> Agraphia is a key localizing sign for a lesion in the <mark>dominant angular gyrus</mark> of the parietal lobe.</li><li><b>Associated Syndrome:</b> It is one of the four classic components of [[38f3ed1f|Gerstmann syndrome]].</li><li><b>Gerstmann Syndrome Tetrad:</b> The full syndrome includes <b>Agraphia</b>, <b>[[8558c64b|Acalculia]]</b> (inability to perform calculations), <b>Finger Agnosia</b> (inability to distinguish fingers), and <b>Left-Right Disorientation</b>.</li><li><b>Alexia with Agraphia:</b> When a patient can neither read nor write, the lesion is typically in the dominant angular gyrus. This is distinct from [[fcf30c1b|alexia without agraphia]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> If a question describes a patient who suddenly cannot write but has no other motor deficits in the hand, and also has trouble with math, think of a dominant parietal lobe lesion, likely from an [[143bb23d|MCA stroke]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Agraphia</b> is not simply poor handwriting; it is a specific neurological deficit in the production of written language that, when paired with [[8558c64b|acalculia]], strongly points to a lesion in the dominant angular gyrus, a hallmark of [[38f3ed1f|Gerstmann syndrome]].</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
