  "0d04bf44": {
    "title": "Akathisia",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Psychiatry",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Neurology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Psychiatry",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Adverse Effects"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Akathisia</b> is a movement disorder characterized by a subjective feeling of inner restlessness and a compelling urge to be in constant motion, most commonly seen as an <i>extrapyramidal side effect</i> of antipsychotic medications.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Most commonly caused by dopamine receptor antagonists, particularly <mark>first-generation (typical) antipsychotics</mark> (e.g., haloperidol). It can also occur with second-generation antipsychotics and some antidepressants.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Patients describe an inability to sit still, feeling like they need to 'jump out of their skin.' Objective signs include pacing, shuffling feet, and shifting from one foot to another.</li><li><b>Timeline:</b> It is a subacute extrapyramidal symptom, typically developing days to weeks after starting or increasing the dose of an offending agent.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> Management involves reducing the dose of the antipsychotic, switching to an agent with a lower risk (e.g., quetiapine), or adding medications like <mark>propranolol</mark>, benzodiazepines, or benztropine.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Differentiate akathisia from psychotic agitation. Akathisia is a drug side effect causing restlessness, while agitation is a symptom of the underlying psychosis. Mistaking one for the other and increasing the antipsychotic dose will worsen akathisia.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Akathisia</b> is a distressing, drug-induced state of motor restlessness that must be distinguished from psychiatric agitation, as the treatment involves reducing or counteracting the offending antipsychotic, not increasing it.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Dopamine (D2) Receptor Blockade] --> B(Disruption of Nigrostriatal Pathway); B --> C[Subjective Restlessness & Compulsion to Move]; C --> D(Akathisia);"
    },
    "connections": [
