    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Alar Plate</b> is the dorsal part of the neural tube in the developing embryo, which differentiates into <i>sensory neurons</i> of the spinal cord and brainstem under the influence of signaling molecules like bone morphogenetic proteins (BMPs).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Location:</b> Dorsal (posterior) region of the developing spinal cord and brainstem.</li><li><b>Function:</b> Gives rise to <u>sensory</u> components of the central nervous system. Mnemonic: Alar is dorsal, like the dorsal fin of a shark which senses things in the water.</li><li><b>Inducing Signal:</b> Development is induced by signaling molecules from the overlying ectoderm, primarily <mark>Bone Morphogenetic Proteins (BMPs)</mark>.</li><li><b>Counterpart:</b> The ventral counterpart is the [[253e3efb|Basal Plate]], which develops into motor neurons under the influence of Sonic Hedgehog (SHH) from the notochord.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the simple orientation: <b>Alar = Sensory = Dorsal</b>, and <b>Basal = Motor = Ventral</b>. This organization persists in the adult spinal cord.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Alar Plate</b> is the embryonic foundation for the sensory pathways of the CNS, establishing the fundamental dorsal-sensory and ventral-motor organization of the neural tube that is maintained throughout life.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Neural Tube] --> B(Alar Plate - Dorsal); A --> C(Basal Plate - Ventral); D[Ectoderm] --BMPs--> B; B --> E[Sensory Neurons]; F[Notochord] --SHH--> C; C --> G[Motor Neurons];"
    },
