  "fcf30c1b": {
    "title": "Alexia",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Cognitive Deficit",
      "Stroke",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Brain Lesions"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Alexia</b> is an acquired neurological disorder characterized by the <i>inability to read or comprehend written language</i>, resulting from a lesion in the brain's language or visual processing centers.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Alexia without Agraphia (Pure Alexia):</b> A specific syndrome where the patient can write but cannot read what they have just written. This is a classic disconnection syndrome.</li><li><b>Lesion Location:</b> Caused by a lesion in the <mark>dominant (usually left) occipital lobe</mark> that also damages the <mark>splenium of the corpus callosum</mark>.</li><li><b>Mechanism:</b> Visual information from the intact right occipital lobe cannot cross over to the dominant hemisphere's language areas (Wernicke's area, angular gyrus) for interpretation because the connecting fibers in the splenium are damaged. The dominant visual cortex is also damaged, so no visual information can be processed on that side.</li><li><b>Vascular Territory:</b> This specific lesion is classically caused by a stroke in the territory of the [[b6a2cc31|Posterior Cerebral Artery (PCA)]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The vignette of a patient who can write a sentence but is unable to read it back is pathognomonic for alexia without agraphia, pointing directly to a left PCA stroke affecting the occipital lobe and splenium.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Alexia without agraphia</b> is a quintessential disconnection syndrome where visual information is stranded in the non-dominant hemisphere, unable to reach the language centers in the dominant hemisphere because the connecting bridge (splenium of the corpus callosum) has been destroyed, typically by a PCA stroke.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Written Word] --> B(Eyes); B --> C[Right Visual Cortex]; C --x D(Splenium of Corpus Callosum); D --x E[Left Language Areas]; B --> F(Left Visual Cortex); F --x G[Lesion];"
    },
