  "083094db": {
    "title": "Alprazolam",
    "primaryType": "drug",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Psychiatry",
      "Neurology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Psychiatry",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Anxiolytics"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Alprazolam</b> (trade name Xanax) is a potent, short-acting <i>benzodiazepine</i> used primarily for the management of anxiety disorders, especially panic disorder, and for the short-term treatment of anxiety associated with depression.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> A positive allosteric modulator of the [[gaba_a_receptor|GABA<sub>A</sub> receptor]]. It increases the <u>frequency</u> of chloride channel opening in response to GABA binding, leading to enhanced CNS inhibition.</li><li><b>Pharmacokinetics:</b> It is short-acting. Mnemonic for short-acting benzodiazepines: <b>ATOM</b> (<b>A</b>lprazolam, <b>T</b>riazolam, <b>O</b>xazepam, <b>M</b>idazolam).</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Primarily for [[panic_disorder|panic disorder]] and [[generalized_anxiety_disorder|generalized anxiety disorder]].</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Sedation, dependence, tolerance, and withdrawal symptoms. Additive CNS depression with other depressants like alcohol and barbiturates. Has a higher addictive potential due to its short half-life.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Because of its rapid onset and short duration, alprazolam is highly effective for acute panic attacks but also carries a high risk of dependence and severe withdrawal. Overdose is treated with [[flumazenil]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Alprazolam</b> is a high-potency, short-acting benzodiazepine that provides rapid relief for panic and anxiety by enhancing GABAergic inhibition, but its pharmacokinetic profile also contributes to a significant risk of dependence and withdrawal.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Alprazolam] --> B(Binds to GABA-A Receptor); B --> C(‚Üë Frequency of Cl- Channel Opening); C --> D(‚Üë Cl- Influx); D --> E(Hyperpolarization of Neuron); E --> F(CNS Depression/Anxiolysis);"
