  "77ae6148": {
    "title": "Alzheimer Disease",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Pathology",
      "Geriatrics",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Dementia"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Alzheimer Disease</b> is the most common cause of <i>dementia</i> in older adults, a progressive neurodegenerative disorder characterized by the extracellular deposition of <b>amyloid-Œ≤ (AŒ≤) plaques</b> and the intracellular accumulation of <b>hyperphosphorylated tau tangles</b>, leading to widespread cortical atrophy and a significant cholinergic deficit.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathology Hallmarks:</b> Extracellular <mark>senile plaques</mark> (composed of AŒ≤) and intracellular <mark>neurofibrillary tangles</mark> (composed of hyperphosphorylated tau protein). The number of tangles correlates with disease severity.</li><li><b>Genetics:</b> Risk is increased by the <mark>ApoE4</mark> allele for the sporadic, late-onset form. Early-onset familial forms are associated with mutations in <i>APP</i> (chromosome 21), <i>presenilin-1</i> (chromosome 14), and <i>presenilin-2</i> (chromosome 1).</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Insidious onset of progressive short-term memory loss, followed by language deficits (aphasia), visuospatial difficulties, and executive dysfunction. Personality and behavioral changes are common in later stages.</li><li><b>Neurotransmitter Deficit:</b> Marked decrease in [[6a005559|acetylcholine]] due to degeneration of cholinergic neurons in the [[361438f2|Basal nucleus of Meynert]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Patients with <b>Down syndrome (Trisomy 21)</b> have a greatly increased risk of early-onset Alzheimer's because the <i>APP</i> gene is located on chromosome 21, leading to a gene dosage effect and increased AŒ≤ production.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The core pathology of <b>Alzheimer Disease</b> involves a dual-proteinopathy of extracellular amyloid plaques and intracellular tau tangles, which together trigger synaptic dysfunction and neuronal death, manifesting clinically as a progressive decline in memory and cognition due to widespread cortical and hippocampal atrophy.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[APP Gene on Chr 21] --Abnormal Cleavage--> B(Amyloid-Œ≤ Monomers); B --> C(Oligomers & Plaques); D[Tau Protein] --Hyperphosphorylation--> E(Neurofibrillary Tangles); C & E --> F(Synaptic Dysfunction & Neuronal Death); F --> G(Cortical Atrophy); G --> H(Dementia);"
