  "9c9679ea": {
    "title": "Amantadine",
    "primaryType": "drug",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Neurology",
      "Infectious Disease",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Parkinson Disease Therapy"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Amantadine</b> is a medication with multiple mechanisms of action, used primarily in neurology to treat [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]] and drug-induced extrapyramidal symptoms, and historically as an antiviral agent for influenza A.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism (Parkinson's):</b> Increases dopamine availability by <mark>enhancing dopamine release</mark> and <mark>inhibiting dopamine reuptake</mark> in the CNS. It also has some anticholinergic properties.</li><li><b>Clinical Use (Neurology):</b> Used for mild [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]] to improve tremor, rigidity, and bradykinesia. It is particularly useful for reducing levodopa-induced dyskinesias in advanced disease. Also used to treat acute dystonia caused by antipsychotics.</li><li><b>Antiviral Use:</b> Previously used for prophylaxis and treatment of Influenza A by blocking the M2 proton channel, but is no longer recommended due to widespread resistance.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> CNS effects like confusion, hallucinations, and dizziness. A characteristic side effect is <mark>livedo reticularis</mark> (a mottled, purplish skin discoloration) and peripheral edema.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> For Parkinson's, amantadine is a 'weaker' drug but can be useful early on or for managing side effects of more potent therapies. The association with livedo reticularis is a classic board question clue.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Amantadine</b> serves a niche role in managing [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]] by modestly increasing dopamine levels, but its utility is limited by CNS side effects and the unique dermatologic finding of livedo reticularis.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
