  "f0aac1c3": {
    "title": "Amaurosis Fugax",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Neurology",
      "Cardiovascular",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Retinal Disorders"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Amaurosis fugax</b> (from Greek for 'darkening' and Latin for 'fleeting') is a painless, <i>transient monocular vision loss</i>, classically described by patients as a <mark>\"curtain coming down over one eye.\"</mark> It is a form of [[623ba776|transient ischemic attack (TIA)]] affecting the retina.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Most commonly caused by an embolus to the [[3334840f|central or branch retinal artery]], which temporarily obstructs blood flow.</li><li><b>Source of Emboli:</b> The most frequent source is an atherosclerotic plaque in the <mark>ipsilateral carotid artery</mark>. It can also be cardiogenic (e.g., from atrial fibrillation).</li><li><b>Clinical Significance:</b> It is a critical warning sign of underlying cerebrovascular disease and portends a high risk of a major [[c5da3c57|stroke]].</li><li><b>Workup:</b> Patients require urgent evaluation, including a carotid ultrasound (duplex) to assess for stenosis and an EKG/echocardiogram to rule out cardiac sources.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A vignette describing a patient with a history of hypertension and hyperlipidemia who experiences a sudden, painless, temporary \"curtain-like\" vision loss in one eye should immediately point to amaurosis fugax secondary to carotid artery disease.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Amaurosis fugax</b> is not just an eye problem but a neurological emergency; this transient 'curtain' of vision loss is a TIA of the retina, most often signaling significant atherosclerotic disease in the ipsilateral carotid artery and a high impending risk of stroke.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Carotid Artery Plaque] --> B(Embolus); B --> C[Ophthalmic Artery]; C --> D[Retinal Artery Occlusion]; D --> E[Transient Monocular Vision Loss]; E --> F(Amaurosis Fugax);"
    },
