  "a4a401c7": {
    "title": "Amblyopia",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Pediatrics",
      "Neurology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Pediatric Ophthalmology"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Amblyopia</b>, commonly known as \"lazy eye,\" is a neurodevelopmental disorder of vision characterized by <i>decreased visual acuity</i> in one or both eyes that is not correctable by refractive means and is not due to any structural eye pathology. It results from abnormal visual experience during early childhood.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> During a critical period of visual development (birth to ~7 years), the brain suppresses or ignores the input from one eye, leading to maldevelopment of the visual cortex corresponding to that eye.</li><li><b>Common Causes:</b><br>1. <b>[[cdcda821|Strabismus]] (Misalignment):</b> The brain ignores the image from the deviating eye to avoid diplopia.<br>2. <b>Anisometropia (Unequal Refractive Error):</b> The brain favors the eye with better focus.<br>3. <b>Deprivation:</b> An obstruction like a congenital [[85f03b02|cataract]] or ptosis blocks a clear image from forming.</li><li><b>Diagnosis:</b> Detected during pediatric vision screening. The key finding is a difference in visual acuity between the two eyes.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> Must be initiated early in the critical period. Treatment involves correcting the underlying cause (e.g., glasses for refractive error, surgery for strabismus/cataract) and then forcing the brain to use the amblyopic eye, typically by <mark>patching the good eye</mark> or using atropine drops to blur its vision.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Early detection and treatment are crucial. If not treated before the end of the critical period (~age 7-8), amblyopia can result in irreversible vision loss.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Amblyopia</b> is a 'brain' problem, not an 'eye' problem; it is the failure of the visual cortex to develop properly due to abnormal input from an eye during a critical developmental window, leading to vision loss that can only be reversed by forcing the brain to pay attention to the 'lazy' eye before that window closes.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_caused_by",
