    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Amino acids</b> are organic compounds that serve as the building blocks of proteins and as precursors for many neurotransmitters. In the central nervous system, their passage from the blood into the brain is tightly regulated by the [[dd47b9cc|blood-brain barrier]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Blood-Brain Barrier Transport:</b> Amino acids are generally lipid-insoluble and cannot diffuse freely across the [[dd47b9cc|blood-brain barrier]]. They require <mark>carrier-mediated transport proteins</mark> to enter the CNS.</li><li><b>Transport Systems:</b> There are specific transporters for different classes of amino acids (e.g., large neutral, basic, acidic). These transporters can become saturated and exhibit competition.</li><li><b>Neurotransmitter Precursors:</b> Many crucial neurotransmitters are synthesized from amino acids that must be transported into the brain. Examples include Tyrosine (precursor to [[90adc821|dopamine]], norepinephrine) and Tryptophan (precursor to [[5d3c2089|serotonin]]).</li><li><b>Clinical Relevance:</b> In disorders like [[phenylketonuria|Phenylketonuria (PKU)]], high levels of one amino acid (phenylalanine) can saturate the large neutral amino acid transporter, impairing the transport of other essential amino acids (like tyrosine and tryptophan) into the brain, contributing to neurological dysfunction.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember that both glucose and amino acids require specific carrier-mediated transport to cross the [[dd47b9cc|blood-brain barrier]]; they do not diffuse freely.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The brain's supply of essential <b>amino acids</b>, critical for both protein synthesis and neurotransmitter production, is entirely dependent on specialized carrier proteins at the [[dd47b9cc|blood-brain barrier]], a system that can be competitively inhibited in certain metabolic diseases.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
