    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Amitriptyline</b> is a <i>tricyclic antidepressant (TCA)</i> that works by inhibiting the reuptake of serotonin and norepinephrine. Due to its significant side effect profile, its primary use has shifted from depression to treating neuropathic pain and providing prophylaxis for [[c8833bae|migraine headaches]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Blocks reuptake of norepinephrine and serotonin. Also has potent antagonistic effects at muscarinic, Œ±1-adrenergic, and H1-histamine receptors, which account for its side effects.</li><li><b>Clinical Use (Neurology):</b> Used for prophylaxis of [[c8833bae|migraine headaches]] and for the management of chronic neuropathic pain (e.g., diabetic neuropathy, postherpetic neuralgia).</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Strong anticholinergic effects (<mark>dry mouth, constipation, urinary retention, confusion</mark>), orthostatic hypotension (Œ±1 blockade), sedation (H1 blockade), and weight gain.</li><li><b>Cardiotoxicity:</b> Overdose is life-threatening, causing QRS widening and ventricular arrhythmias due to Na<sup>+</sup> channel blockade. Treat with sodium bicarbonate.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the 'Tri-C's' for TCA toxicity: <b>C</b>onvulsions, <b>C</b>oma, <b>C</b>ardiotoxicity. Amitriptyline is a tertiary amine TCA, giving it more potent anticholinergic and antihistaminic effects compared to secondary amines like nortriptyline.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Amitriptyline</b>, a classic TCA, is now more valued for its role in migraine prevention and neuropathic pain than for depression, but its use is always tempered by a significant burden of anticholinergic, antihistaminic, and anti-adrenergic side effects, with cardiotoxicity being the most dangerous in overdose.</p>",
