    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Amnesia</b> is a deficit in memory caused by brain damage, disease, or psychological trauma. It can be categorized based on the temporal nature of the memory loss relative to the causative event.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Anterograde Amnesia:</b> The inability to form <u>new</u> memories after the event that caused the amnesia. Long-term memories from before the event remain intact.</li><li><b>Anterograde Lesion Site:</b> Classically caused by bilateral damage to the <mark>hippocampus</mark>, a key structure in the medial temporal lobe for memory consolidation. Seen in [[77ae6148|Alzheimer disease]] and [[herpes_simplex_encephalitis|herpes simplex encephalitis]].</li><li><b>Retrograde Amnesia:</b> The loss of memories that were formed <u>before</u> the onset of amnesia.</li><li><b>Korsakoff Syndrome:</b> A classic example of a syndrome causing both anterograde and retrograde amnesia, along with confabulation. It is caused by thiamine (B1) deficiency, often in the context of chronic alcohol use, and involves damage to the <mark>mammillary bodies</mark> and thalamus.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Bilateral hippocampal lesions (e.g., from an anoxic brain injury or HSV encephalitis) are the classic cause of profound anterograde amnesia. The patient can remember their childhood but not what they had for breakfast.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The hippocampus is the brain's 'save button' for new memories; therefore, bilateral damage to this structure results in profound <b>anterograde amnesia</b>, leaving the individual unable to consolidate new experiences into long-term memory.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Brain Injury/Disease] --> B{Amnesia}; B --> C[Anterograde Amnesia]; C --> D(Inability to form new memories); D --> E[Lesion: Hippocampus]; B --> F[Retrograde Amnesia]; F --> G(Loss of past memories); G --> H[Lesion: Widespread Cortex];"
    },
