      "Limbic System"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Amygdala</b> is an almond-shaped set of neurons located deep within the medial temporal lobe of the brain. It is a key component of the [[73ace357|limbic system]] and plays a central role in processing emotions, particularly fear, anxiety, and aggression, as well as in memory formation and decision-making.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Function:</b> The amygdala is the brain's emotional center, responsible for processing fear, pleasure, and anger. It links emotions to memories and influences social and sexual behavior.</li><li><b>Location:</b> Situated in the medial temporal lobe, anterior to the [[a0590674|hippocampus]].</li><li><b>Lesion Effects (Bilateral):</b> Bilateral destruction of the amygdala results in <mark>Kl√ºver-Bucy syndrome</mark>.</li><li><b>Kl√ºver-Bucy Syndrome:</b> Characterized by disinhibited behavior, including hyperorality (tendency to examine objects with the mouth), hypersexuality, hyperphagia, and visual agnosia. Patients also exhibit placidity (loss of fear response).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The classic cause of bilateral amygdala damage leading to Kl√ºver-Bucy syndrome is [[herpes_simplex_encephalitis|Herpes Simplex Virus-1 (HSV-1) encephalitis]], which has a predilection for the temporal lobes.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Amygdala</b> acts as the brain's alarm system and emotional processor; its bilateral destruction unleashes primitive behaviors by removing the normal emotional filters, resulting in the dramatic and disinhibited presentation of Kl√ºver-Bucy syndrome.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Sensory Input] --> B(Amygdala); B --Fear/Emotion Processing--> C[Hypothalamus & Brainstem]; C --> D(Autonomic & Behavioral Response);"
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_part_of",
        "to": "73ace357"
      },
      {
        "type": "bilateral_lesion_causes",
        "to": "kluver_bucy_syndrome"
      },
      {
