  "b374ebd6": {
    "title": "Cerebral Amyloid Angiopathy",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Pathology",
      "Geriatrics",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Cerebrovascular Disease"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Cerebral Amyloid Angiopathy (CAA)</b> is a condition in which amyloid-Œ≤ protein deposits in the walls of small to medium-sized arteries of the cerebral cortex and leptomeninges, weakening the vessels and increasing the risk of spontaneous, recurrent <mark>lobar</mark> intraparenchymal hemorrhages.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Deposition of <mark>amyloid-Œ≤</mark> (the same protein found in [[77ae6148|Alzheimer's]] plaques) in the tunica media and adventitia of cortical and leptomeningeal vessels.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Most commonly presents with recurrent, spontaneous lobar hemorrhages in older adults (>65 years). These hemorrhages are typically located in the superficial cortex (lobar) rather than deep structures like the basal ganglia.</li><li><b>Location:</b> Hemorrhages are characteristically <mark>lobar</mark> (frontal, parietal, occipital, temporal lobes), contrasting with hypertensive hemorrhages which are typically deep (basal ganglia, thalamus, pons).</li><li><b>Association:</b> Strongly associated with [[77ae6148|Alzheimer disease]], although it can occur independently.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> An elderly patient with no history of significant hypertension who presents with a spontaneous, superficial (lobar) intracerebral hemorrhage should raise high suspicion for Cerebral Amyloid Angiopathy. Recurrent hemorrhages in different lobes are a key feature.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Cerebral Amyloid Angiopathy</b> is a major cause of lobar intracerebral hemorrhage in the elderly, resulting from amyloid-Œ≤ deposition that makes cortical blood vessels brittle and prone to rupture, distinct from the deep brain hemorrhages typically caused by hypertension.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Amyloid-Œ≤ Deposition] --> B(Vessel Wall Weakening); B --> C[Cortical & Leptomeningeal Arteries]; C --> D(Rupture); D --> E[Recurrent Lobar Hemorrhage];"
    },
    "connections": [
