  "4ed629f9": {
    "title": "Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS)",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Pathology",
      "Degenerative Disease",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Motor Neuron Diseases"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS)</b>, also known as Lou Gehrig's disease, is a relentless and fatal neurodegenerative disorder characterized by the progressive loss of both <u>upper motor neurons</u> (in the motor cortex) and <u>lower motor neurons</u> (in the brainstem and spinal cord).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Degeneration of corticospinal tracts (lateral sclerosis) and anterior horn cells (amyotrophy). The exact cause is unknown in most cases (sporadic), but some familial cases are linked to a mutation in the <mark>superoxide dismutase 1 (SOD1)</mark> gene.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> A hallmark of ALS is the combination of both <b>upper motor neuron (UMN)</b> signs (spasticity, hyperreflexia, Babinski sign) and <b>lower motor neuron (LMN)</b> signs (fasciculations, atrophy, flaccid weakness).</li><li><b>Symptoms:</b> Can present with asymmetric limb weakness (e.g., foot drop, hand weakness), dysarthria (difficulty speaking), and dysphagia (difficulty swallowing). Sensation, cognition, and eye movements are typically spared.</li><li><b>Bulbar Involvement:</b> When LMNs in the brainstem are affected, it leads to [[901f3180|bulbar palsy]], causing dysarthria, dysphagia, and tongue fasciculations.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> [[riluzole|Riluzole]], a glutamate antagonist, may modestly increase survival. Management is largely supportive, focusing on respiratory support and nutrition.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The combination of UMN and LMN signs in the same patient is the key to diagnosing ALS. Look for a patient with weakness and atrophy in one arm (LMN) but hyperreflexia in the legs (UMN).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis</b> is uniquely devastating because it attacks the entire voluntary motor system, from the brain to the muscle, combining the spasticity of UMN lesions with the muscle wasting of LMN lesions, while cruelly sparing the patient's intellect and senses.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[UMN Degeneration - Motor Cortex] --> B(Spasticity, Hyperreflexia); C[LMN Degeneration - Anterior Horn] --> D(Fasciculations, Atrophy); A & C --> E(Progressive Motor Weakness);"
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_a_type_of",
        "to": "motor_neuron_disease"
      },
      {
        "type": "presents_with",
        "to": "upper_motor_neuron_signs"
