    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Anal Wink Reflex</b> is a superficial reflex involving the contraction of the external anal sphincter upon stroking the skin around the anus. It is used to test the integrity of the <mark>S3 and S4</mark> spinal nerve roots and the pudendal nerve.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Nerve Roots:</b> Tests the integrity of the <b>S3-S4</b> spinal cord segments. Mnemonic: S2, 3, 4 keep the penis off the floor (for erection), and S3, 4 are for the anal wink.</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> Stroking the perianal skin stimulates afferent fibers of the pudendal nerve. The signal travels to the S3-S4 spinal segments, synapses, and an efferent signal returns via the pudendal nerve to cause contraction of the external anal sphincter.</li><li><b>Clinical Significance:</b> An absent anal wink reflex is a key sign in <mark>[[2904b5c8|Cauda Equina Syndrome]]</mark>, a neurosurgical emergency. It indicates damage to the S3-S4 nerve roots.</li><li><b>Other Conditions:</b> The reflex may also be absent in other conditions affecting the sacral nerve roots or spinal cord, such as spinal cord injury or spina bifida.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> In a patient with severe low back pain, saddle anesthesia, and bowel/bladder dysfunction, checking for the anal wink reflex is a critical step. Its absence strongly supports the diagnosis of [[2904b5c8|Cauda Equina Syndrome]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Anal Wink Reflex</b> is a simple but vital physical exam maneuver for assessing the function of the lower sacral nerve roots (S3-S4); its absence is a red flag for [[2904b5c8|Cauda Equina Syndrome]].</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Stroke Perianal Skin] --> B(Afferent Signal via Pudendal N.); B --> C[S3-S4 Spinal Cord]; C --> D(Efferent Signal via Pudendal N.); D --> E(External Anal Sphincter Contraction);"
    },
    "connections": [
