    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Anencephaly</b> is a severe and lethal congenital malformation, classified as an open <i>neural tube defect</i>, resulting from the failure of the rostral (anterior) neuropore to close during the 4th week of embryonic development. This leads to the absence of the forebrain and a large portion of the skull (calvarium).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Failure of the rostral neuropore to close leads to an open calvarium and absence of the forebrain. The remaining brain tissue is exposed and degenerates.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Incompatible with postnatal life; infants are stillborn or die shortly after birth. The fetus has a characteristic <mark>\"frog-like appearance\"</mark> due to the absent cranial vault.</li><li><b>Maternal Findings:</b> Associated with <mark>polyhydramnios</mark> due to impaired fetal swallowing, as the neural control for swallowing is absent.</li><li><b>Diagnosis:</b> Can be detected prenatally via ultrasound. Maternal serum screening will show markedly <mark>elevated alpha-fetoprotein (AFP)</mark>. Amniotic fluid will also have elevated AFP and acetylcholinesterase (AChE).</li><li><b>Prevention:</b> Risk is significantly reduced by maternal folic acid supplementation before conception and during early pregnancy.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Anencephaly</b> represents a catastrophic failure of early neural development, where the absence of the forebrain and skull results in a condition incompatible with life, and is prenatally indicated by elevated maternal AFP and polyhydramnios.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Failure of Rostral Neuropore Closure] --> B(Absence of Forebrain & Calvarium); B --> C(Polyhydramnios); B --> D(Lethal Outcome);"
    },
    "connections": [
