  "a5295f1a": {
    "title": "Anesthetics",
    "primaryType": "concept",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Anesthesiology",
      "Neurology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Anesthetics"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Anesthetics</b> are drugs that induce a reversible loss of sensation. They are broadly classified into <i>general anesthetics</i>, which cause a reversible loss of consciousness, and <i>local anesthetics</i>, which block nerve transmission in a specific region of the body.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>General Anesthetics:</b> Induce a state of unconsciousness, analgesia, amnesia, and muscle relaxation. They can be inhaled (e.g., sevoflurane, desflurane) or intravenous (e.g., propofol, ketamine, etomidate). Their potency is measured by the <mark>Minimum Alveolar Concentration (MAC)</mark>.</li><li><b>Local Anesthetics:</b> Block nerve conduction by inhibiting voltage-gated Na<sup>+</sup> channels. They are classified as esters (e.g., procaine, cocaine) or amides (e.g., lidocaine, bupivacaine). They are weak bases and are less effective in infected (acidic) tissue.</li><li><b>Neuromuscular Blockers:</b> Often used with general anesthetics to achieve profound muscle relaxation (paralysis). They can be depolarizing (e.g., succinylcholine) or non-depolarizing (e.g., rocuronium).</li><li><b>Malignant Hyperthermia:</b> A rare, life-threatening hypermetabolic state triggered by inhaled anesthetics (except N<sub>2</sub>O) and succinylcholine in genetically susceptible individuals. Treated with [[dantrolene]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Understand the key pharmacokinetic properties of inhaled anesthetics: low blood solubility (low blood:gas partition coefficient) leads to rapid induction and recovery, while high lipid solubility (high oil:gas partition coefficient) corresponds to high potency (low MAC).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The field of <b>anesthesia</b> relies on a combination of drugs to achieve a balanced state of unconsciousness, analgesia, and muscle relaxation, with general anesthetics acting on the CNS to induce sleep and local anesthetics acting on peripheral nerves to block pain signals.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "includes",
        "to": "general_anesthetics"
      },
      {
        "type": "includes",
        "to": "local_anesthetics"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_associated_with",
        "to": "malignant_hyperthermia"
      }
    ]
  },
  "a7f97d7f": {
    "title": "Cerebral Aneurysms",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Neurosurgery",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Cerebrovascular Disease"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Cerebral aneurysms</b> are localized, abnormal dilations of blood vessels in the brain, which carry a significant risk of rupture, leading to life-threatening intracranial hemorrhage.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Saccular (Berry) Aneurysms:</b> Most common type. Thin-walled outpouchings, typically occurring at arterial branch points in the [[e22300e8|Circle of Willis]]. Most common site is the junction of the [[bd802d22|anterior communicating artery]] and anterior cerebral artery. Rupture causes [[63f8b05f|subarachnoid hemorrhage]].</li><li><b>Associations with Saccular Aneurysms:</b> <mark>Autosomal Dominant Polycystic Kidney Disease (ADPKD)</mark>, Ehlers-Danlos syndrome, Marfan syndrome, hypertension, smoking.</li><li><b>Charcot-Bouchard Microaneurysms:</b> Aneurysms of small, penetrating arteries (e.g., lenticulostriate arteries) associated with chronic hypertension. Rupture causes [[70b266c8|intraparenchymal hemorrhage]], typically in deep brain structures like the basal ganglia or thalamus.</li><li><b>Rupture Presentation:</b> Rupture of a saccular aneurysm classically presents as a sudden, severe <mark>\"worst headache of my life\"</mark> (thunderclap headache), indicating a [[63f8b05f|subarachnoid hemorrhage]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient with ADPKD who develops a sudden, severe headache should be immediately evaluated for a ruptured berry aneurysm. A PCom aneurysm can compress CN III, causing a 'down and out' eye with a 'blown' (dilated) pupil.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>Cerebral aneurysms are focal weaknesses in brain arteries; the larger <b>saccular (berry) aneurysms</b> at the Circle of Willis rupture into the subarachnoid space, while the smaller <b>Charcot-Bouchard microaneurysms</b> in deep brain structures rupture due to hypertension, causing intraparenchymal bleeds.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Cerebral Aneurysm] --> B{Types}; B --> C[Saccular/Berry]; C --> D(Circle of Willis); D --> E[Rupture -> Subarachnoid Hemorrhage]; B --> F[Charcot-Bouchard]; F --> G(Small Penetrating Arteries); G --> H[Rupture -> Intraparenchymal Hemorrhage];"
    },
