  "ed8c1c37": {
    "title": "Anhidrosis in Horner Syndrome",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Autonomic",
      "Dermatology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Autonomic Disorders"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Anhidrosis</b>, the inability to sweat normally, is one of the three classic signs of [[c19010a3|Horner syndrome]], resulting from the disruption of sympathetic innervation to the sweat glands of the face.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Horner Syndrome Triad:</b> The full triad is <b>Ptosis</b> (mild eyelid droop), <b>Miosis</b> (constricted pupil), and <b>Anhidrosis</b> (decreased sweating).</li><li><b>Mechanism:</b> Disruption of the oculosympathetic pathway prevents the release of acetylcholine from postganglionic sympathetic neurons that innervate sweat glands (a sympathetic exception).</li><li><b>Localization Value:</b> The distribution of anhidrosis can help localize the lesion in the three-neuron sympathetic chain.</li><li><b>Lesion Localization:</b><br> - <b>1st Order (Central):</b> Lesion in hypothalamus or brainstem/spinal cord. Anhidrosis affects the entire ipsilateral half of the body.<br> - <b>2nd Order (Preganglionic):</b> Lesion in the chest (e.g., Pancoast tumor). Anhidrosis affects the ipsilateral face and neck.<br> - <b>3rd Order (Postganglionic):</b> Lesion above the superior cervical ganglion (e.g., carotid dissection). Anhidrosis is often minimal or absent, affecting only a small patch on the forehead, because fibers to most facial sweat glands travel with the external carotid artery.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A painful Horner syndrome (especially with neck pain) should raise suspicion for a carotid artery dissection, a 3rd order neuron lesion where anhidrosis is often absent.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>While part of the classic triad, the presence and distribution of <b>anhidrosis</b> in [[c19010a3|Horner syndrome]] is a subtle but powerful clue for localizing the lesion along the long oculosympathetic pathway, with widespread anhidrosis suggesting a central lesion and absent anhidrosis pointing towards a postganglionic (3rd order) problem.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_a_sign_of",
        "to": "c19010a3"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_caused_by",
        "to": "sympathetic_pathway_disruption"
      }
    ]
  },
  "830c856c": {
    "title": "Anterior Cerebral Artery (ACA)",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroanatomy",
      "Cerebrovascular",
      "Neurology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Cerebral Vasculature"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Anterior Cerebral Artery (ACA)</b> is a major artery of the brain that branches from the internal carotid artery and supplies the medial portion of the frontal and parietal lobes, as well as the corpus callosum.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Origin:</b> Arises from the bifurcation of the internal carotid artery. The left and right ACAs are connected by the [[bd802d22|anterior communicating artery]].</li><li><b>Territory Supplied:</b> Supplies the medial surface of the cerebral hemispheres. Based on the motor and sensory homunculus, this corresponds to the <mark>lower extremities</mark>.</li><li><b>Stroke Syndrome:</b> Occlusion of the ACA results in a characteristic stroke syndrome with <mark>contralateral motor and sensory deficits predominantly affecting the lower limb</mark> (leg > arm/face).</li><li><b>Other Stroke Signs:</b> May also cause urinary incontinence due to damage to the paracentral lobule. Frontal lobe signs like abulia (lack of will/initiative) or personality changes can occur.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The key to identifying an ACA stroke is the disproportionate weakness and sensory loss in the contralateral leg compared to the arm and face. This contrasts sharply with an [[143bb23d|MCA stroke]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Anterior Cerebral Artery</b> is responsible for the medial brain territory, meaning its occlusion uniquely manifests as a stroke that 'kicks the leg out' from under the patient, with motor and sensory deficits primarily affecting the contralateral lower extremity.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Internal Carotid Artery] --> B(Anterior Cerebral Artery); B --> C(Supplies Medial Cortex); C --> D(Motor/Sensory Homunculus for Leg); B --Connects via AComA--> E(Contralateral ACA);"
    },
    "connections": [
