  "3c4b0ef7": {
    "title": "Anterior Circulation Strokes",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Cerebrovascular",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Cerebrovascular Disease"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Anterior circulation strokes</b> are ischemic events caused by occlusion of the internal carotid artery or its major branches, the [[830c856c|anterior cerebral artery (ACA)]] and the [[143bb23d|middle cerebral artery (MCA)]], leading to deficits related to the cerebral hemispheres.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Vessels Involved:</b> Internal carotid artery (ICA), [[143bb23d|Middle Cerebral Artery (MCA)]], [[830c856c|Anterior Cerebral Artery (ACA)]].</li><li><b>MCA Stroke:</b> The most common type of ischemic stroke. Presents with <mark>contralateral hemiparesis and sensory loss affecting the face and upper limb more than the lower limb</mark>. If the dominant (usually left) hemisphere is affected, it causes [[6bc9a567|aphasia]] (Broca's or Wernicke's). If the non-dominant hemisphere is affected, it causes hemineglect.</li><li><b>ACA Stroke:</b> Presents with <mark>contralateral hemiparesis and sensory loss affecting the lower limb more than the upper limb</mark>. May also cause urinary incontinence and frontal lobe signs (e.g., personality changes, abulia).</li><li><b>Distinction:</b> The key differentiator is the distribution of weakness based on the homunculus: MCA strokes affect the face/arm, while ACA strokes affect the leg.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Aphasia is a 'cortical sign' that strongly points to an MCA stroke in the dominant hemisphere. Leg weakness greater than arm weakness is the classic sign of an ACA stroke.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Anterior circulation strokes</b> produce deficits that can be precisely localized by understanding the functional anatomy of the cerebral cortex and the homunculus; MCA strokes paralyze the contralateral face and arm, while ACA strokes paralyze the contralateral leg.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Internal Carotid Artery] --> B(MCA); B --> C(Contralateral Face/Arm Deficits, Aphasia/Neglect); A --> D(ACA); D --> E(Contralateral Leg Deficits, Incontinence);"
    },
    "connections": [
