  "bd802d22": {
    "title": "Anterior Communicating Artery (AComA)",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroanatomy",
      "Cerebrovascular",
      "Neurology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Cerebral Vasculature"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Anterior Communicating Artery (AComA)</b> is a short blood vessel that connects the left and right [[830c856c|anterior cerebral arteries]], forming the anterior aspect of the [[e22300e8|Circle of Willis]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Function:</b> Provides collateral blood flow between the two anterior cerebral circulations.</li><li><b>Clinical Significance:</b> It is the <mark>most common site</mark> for the formation of saccular (berry) aneurysms in the brain.</li><li><b>Aneurysm Complications:</b><br>1. <b>Rupture:</b> Leads to [[63f8b05f|subarachnoid hemorrhage]], presenting as a \"worst headache of my life.\"<br>2. <b>Compression:</b> A large, unruptured aneurysm can compress the adjacent <mark>optic chiasm</mark>, causing a [[6c3a980e|bitemporal hemianopia]] (tunnel vision).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> When a question mentions a saccular aneurysm, the AComA should be the first location you consider. If the patient has visual field defects, especially bitemporal hemianopia, an AComA aneurysm is a very likely cause.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Anterior Communicating Artery</b>, while small, is clinically significant as the number one location for berry aneurysms, which can either rupture catastrophically into the subarachnoid space or compress the optic chiasm, causing tunnel vision.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Left ACA] -- AComA --> B[Right ACA]; C(AComA Aneurysm) --> D(Rupture -> SAH); C --> E(Compression -> Bitemporal Hemianopia);"
    },
