    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Anterior Inferior Cerebellar Artery (AICA)</b> is an artery in the brain that arises from the basilar artery and supplies blood to the anterior inferior portion of the cerebellum, as well as parts of the lateral pons.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Origin:</b> Typically arises from the lower third of the basilar artery.</li><li><b>Territory Supplied:</b> Lateral pons, middle and inferior cerebellar peduncles, and the anterior inferior cerebellum. It also gives rise to the labyrinthine artery in most individuals, which supplies the inner ear.</li><li><b>Stroke Syndrome:</b> Occlusion of the AICA causes <mark>Lateral Pontine Syndrome</mark>.</li><li><b>Symptoms of AICA Stroke:</b> Mnemonic <b>AICA</b>: <b>A</b>taxia (ipsilateral, from cerebellar peduncle damage), <b>I</b>psilateral facial paralysis (CN VII nucleus/fibers) and deafness/vertigo (CN VIII nucleus/labyrinthine artery), <b>C</b>ontralateral pain/temp loss (spinothalamic tract), <b>A</b>utonomic signs (ipsilateral Horner syndrome).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The key to distinguishing an AICA stroke from a PICA stroke (Lateral Medullary Syndrome) is the presence of <mark>facial paralysis</mark> and <mark>deafness</mark>, which are specific to the pontine location of the AICA territory.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>Occlusion of the <b>Anterior Inferior Cerebellar Artery</b> results in Lateral Pontine Syndrome, a complex brainstem stroke characterized by a unique combination of cerebellar signs, contralateral body sensory loss, and ipsilateral facial deficits including paralysis and deafness, which localizes the lesion squarely to the lateral pons.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Basilar Artery] --> B(AICA); B --> C(Lateral Pons); B --> D(Anterior Inferior Cerebellum); B --> E(Labyrinthine Artery); C --> F(CN VII & VIII Nuclei); E --> G(Inner Ear);"
