    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Anterior Spinal Artery (ASA)</b> is a major artery that supplies the anterior two-thirds of the spinal cord. It originates from the vertebral arteries in the cranium and descends along the anterior surface of the spinal cord.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Origin:</b> Formed from the union of two branches of the vertebral arteries.</li><li><b>Territory Supplied:</b> Supplies the anterior two-thirds of the spinal cord, including the anterior and lateral corticospinal tracts, the spinothalamic tracts, and the anterior horns. It notably <u>spares</u> the [[e7f5cbbe|dorsal columns]].</li><li><b>Stroke Syndrome (Spinal Cord):</b> Occlusion causes <mark>[[b48b54d7|Anterior Spinal Artery Syndrome]]</mark>, characterized by bilateral loss of motor function (flaccid paralysis at the level, UMN signs below) and pain/temperature sensation below the level of the lesion, with <mark>preserved proprioception and vibration sense</mark>.</li><li><b>Stroke Syndrome (Medulla):</b> Occlusion of paramedian branches of the ASA or vertebral arteries causes <mark>Medial Medullary Syndrome</mark>.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The key to identifying an ASA stroke is the dissociation of sensory loss: pain and temperature are gone, but vibration and position sense are intact because the dorsal columns are spared.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Anterior Spinal Artery</b> is the lifeline for the motor and pain/temperature pathways of the spinal cord; its occlusion creates a devastating syndrome of bilateral paralysis and sensory loss, sparing only the dorsal columns' functions of vibration and proprioception.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Vertebral Arteries] --> B(Anterior Spinal Artery); B --> C(Anterior 2/3 of Spinal Cord); C --> D[Corticospinal Tracts]; C --> E[Spinothalamic Tracts]; C --> F[Anterior Horns];"
    },
