    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Anterior Spinal Artery Syndrome</b> is a spinal cord infarct resulting from occlusion of the [[1430f5b4|anterior spinal artery (ASA)]], which leads to ischemia of the anterior two-thirds of the spinal cord, causing a distinct pattern of neurological deficits below the level of the lesion.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Caused by occlusion of the ASA, which can result from aortic surgery (e.g., repair of an aneurysm), severe hypotension (watershed infarct), or thromboembolism.</li><li><b>Structures Damaged:</b> Corticospinal tracts, spinothalamic tracts, and anterior horns.</li><li><b>Structures Spared:</b> The <mark>[[e7f5cbbe|dorsal columns]]</mark> are spared due to their separate blood supply from the posterior spinal arteries.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b><br> - <b>Motor:</b> Bilateral flaccid paralysis at the level of the lesion (LMN signs from anterior horn damage) and bilateral spastic paralysis below the lesion (UMN signs from corticospinal tract damage).<br> - <b>Sensory:</b> Bilateral loss of pain and temperature sensation below the lesion (spinothalamic tract damage).<br> - <b>Sensation Preserved:</b> <mark>Proprioception, vibration, and fine touch are intact</mark> because the dorsal columns are spared.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The dissociation between loss of pain/temperature and preservation of vibration/proprioception is the pathognomonic feature of this syndrome.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Anterior Spinal Artery Syndrome</b> creates a stark neurological divide, paralyzing the body and eliminating pain and temperature sensation below the lesion, while leaving the sense of position and vibration completely intact, a direct reflection of the spinal cord's vascular territories.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[ASA Occlusion] --> B(Infarct of Anterior 2/3 of Spinal Cord); B --> C[Damage to Corticospinal & Spinothalamic Tracts]; B --Spares--> D[Dorsal Columns]; C --> E[Bilateral Paralysis & Loss of Pain/Temp]; D --> F[Preserved Vibration/Proprioception];"
