    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Anti-CGRP monoclonal antibodies</b> are a class of medications used for the prophylactic treatment of [[c8833bae|migraine headaches]]. They work by targeting either calcitonin gene-related peptide (CGRP) itself or its receptor, which are key players in the pathophysiology of migraines.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> These monoclonal antibodies bind to either the CGRP ligand (e.g., eptinezumab, fremanezumab, galcanezumab) or the CGRP receptor (e.g., erenumab), preventing CGRP from mediating its effects of vasodilation and pain transmission in the trigeminal nervous system.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Used for the <mark>prevention (prophylaxis)</mark> of episodic and chronic [[c8833bae|migraines]]. They are not used for acute treatment.</li><li><b>Administration:</b> Administered via subcutaneous injection or IV infusion, typically on a monthly or quarterly basis.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Generally well-tolerated. The most common side effects are injection site reactions. Constipation is notably associated with the CGRP receptor antagonists (e.g., erenumab).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Recognize these drugs by their '-mab' suffix and their specific use for migraine <u>prophylaxis</u>. They represent a targeted therapy based on the modern understanding of migraine pathophysiology involving CGRP.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Anti-CGRP monoclonal antibodies</b> represent a major advance in migraine prevention, offering a highly specific mechanism that directly neutralizes the CGRP pathway, a key driver of pain and inflammation in migraine attacks.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Trigeminal Nerve Activation] --> B(Release of CGRP); B --> C(CGRP Receptor); C --> D(Vasodilation & Pain Transmission); D --> E(Migraine); F[Anti-CGRP mAbs] --x B; G[Anti-CGRP Receptor mAbs] --x C;"
