    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Anticonvulsants</b>, also known as antiepileptic drugs (AEDs), are a diverse group of medications used to treat epileptic [[64c08e92|seizures]]. They work by various mechanisms to suppress the rapid and excessive firing of neurons that initiate a seizure.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Major Mechanisms:</b><br>1. <b>Na<sup>+</sup> Channel Blockade:</b> [[5aea213f|Phenytoin]], [[eddd2bc5|Carbamazepine]], [[0d37e045|Valproate]], [[08d19a8f|Lamotrigine]].<br>2. <b>Enhancement of GABAergic inhibition:</b> Benzodiazepines, Barbiturates, [[valproic_acid|Valproate]].<br>3. <b>Ca<sup>2+</sup> Channel Blockade:</b> [[a90f6fb4|Ethosuximide]] (T-type), Gabapentinoids.</li><li><b>Spectrum of Activity:</b><br> - <b>Broad-spectrum:</b> [[valproic_acid|Valproic acid]], [[08d19a8f|lamotrigine]], [[2341f9c0|levetiracetam]], [[e1f5066c|topiramate]]. Effective for both focal and generalized seizures.<br> - <b>Narrow-spectrum:</b> [[eddd2bc5|Carbamazepine]], [[5aea213f|phenytoin]], gabapentinoids. Primarily for focal seizures. [[a90f6fb4|Ethosuximide]] is for absence seizures only.</li><li><b>Other Uses:</b> Many anticonvulsants are also used for bipolar disorder, neuropathic pain, and [[c8833bae|migraine]] prophylaxis. Some are used in [[45dd6d19|multiple sclerosis]] for symptomatic treatment.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Common side effects include sedation, dizziness, and ataxia. Many carry a risk of serious skin reactions like <mark>Stevens-Johnson syndrome (SJS)</mark>, especially lamotrigine and carbamazepine. All are potentially teratogenic.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Know the first-line treatments for specific seizure types: Absence -> [[a90f6fb4|Ethosuximide]]; Tonic-clonic -> [[valproic_acid|Valproic acid]], [[2341f9c0|levetiracetam]]; Status epilepticus -> Benzodiazepines.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Anticonvulsants</b> primarily work by either dampening neuronal excitability (e.g., blocking Na<sup>+</sup> channels) or enhancing neuronal inhibition (e.g., potentiating GABA), with the choice of drug critically depending on the type of seizure being treated.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
