  "290a966b": {
    "title": "Antidiuretic Hormone (ADH)",
    "primaryType": "molecule",
    "tags": [
      "Endocrinology",
      "Renal",
      "Physiology",
      "Neurology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Endocrine",
      "Physiology",
      "Hypothalamic-Pituitary Axis"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Antidiuretic Hormone (ADH)</b>, also known as vasopressin, is a peptide hormone synthesized in the [[89e86633|hypothalamus]] and released from the posterior pituitary. Its primary functions are to regulate plasma osmolality by increasing water reabsorption in the kidneys and to regulate blood pressure via vasoconstriction.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Synthesis & Release:</b> Synthesized primarily in the <mark>supraoptic nucleus</mark> of the [[89e86633|hypothalamus]], transported down axons, and stored/released from the posterior pituitary (neurohypophysis).</li><li><b>Regulation:</b> Release is stimulated by <mark>increased plasma osmolality</mark> (detected by osmoreceptors in the hypothalamus) and, to a lesser extent, by decreased blood volume/pressure.</li><li><b>Renal Action (V2 Receptors):</b> Binds to V2 receptors on the basolateral membrane of principal cells in the renal collecting ducts. This activates a G<sub>s</sub>-cAMP pathway, leading to the insertion of <mark>aquaporin-2</mark> channels into the apical membrane, increasing water reabsorption.</li><li><b>Vascular Action (V1 Receptors):</b> Binds to V1 receptors on vascular smooth muscle, activating a G<sub>q</sub>-IP<sub>3</sub>/DAG pathway that causes vasoconstriction and increases blood pressure.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Pathologies are key: Deficiency of ADH or its receptor causes [[diabetes_insipidus]]. Excess ADH secretion causes [[syndrome_of_inappropriate_antidiuretic_hormone|SIADH]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Antidiuretic Hormone</b> is the body's primary regulator of water balance, acting on the kidney's collecting ducts via V2 receptors to conserve water when osmolality is high, and on blood vessels via V1 receptors to raise blood pressure when volume is low.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[‚Üë Plasma Osmolality] --> B(Hypothalamus); B --> C(Posterior Pituitary); C --Release ADH--> D; D --V2 Receptor--> E[Kidney Collecting Duct]; E --> F(‚Üë Aquaporin-2 Insertion); F --> G(‚Üë Water Reabsorption); D --V1 Receptor--> H[Vascular Smooth Muscle]; H --> I(Vasoconstriction);"
    },
