    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Antimuscarinic drugs</b>, also known as anticholinergics, are a class of medications that act as competitive antagonists at muscarinic acetylcholine receptors, thereby blocking the effects of the parasympathetic nervous system.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Competitively block [[6a005559|acetylcholine]] at muscarinic receptors (M1, M2, M3). They do not affect nicotinic receptors.</li><li><b>Clinical Effects (Mnemonic):</b> \"Hot as a hare, dry as a bone, blind as a bat, red as a beet, mad as a hatter.\"<br> - <b>Dry:</b> ‚Üì Salivation, lacrimation, sweating.<br> - <b>Blind:</b> Mydriasis (pupil dilation) and cycloplegia (loss of accommodation).<br> - <b>Hot & Red:</b> ‚Üì Sweating leads to hyperthermia and compensatory flushing.<br> - <b>Mad:</b> CNS effects like delirium, confusion, hallucinations (especially with drugs that cross the BBB).</li><li><b>Neurologic Use:</b> Used in [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]] (e.g., [[383f6fbe|benztropine]], trihexyphenidyl) to treat tremor and rigidity by rebalancing the cholinergic-dopaminergic systems. Also used to treat drug-induced extrapyramidal symptoms.</li><li><b>Other Uses:</b> Atropine (bradycardia), scopolamine (motion sickness), ipratropium (COPD), oxybutynin (overactive bladder).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Be cautious using antimuscarinics in the elderly due to increased risk of confusion, hallucinations, and delirium. They are contraindicated in [[9c80344d|angle-closure glaucoma]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Antimuscarinic drugs</b> function by blocking the 'rest and digest' functions of the parasympathetic nervous system, leading to a predictable constellation of side effects that are essentially the opposite of a cholinergic toxidrome.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Acetylcholine] --x B(Antimuscarinic Drugs); B --x C(Muscarinic Receptors); C --x D(Parasympathetic Effects);"
    },
