    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Antispasmodics</b>, or skeletal muscle relaxants, are a group of drugs used to alleviate symptoms associated with muscle spasticity or acute muscle spasms by acting either on the central nervous system or directly on the muscle.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Baclofen:</b> A [[gaba_b_receptor|GABA<sub>B</sub> receptor]] agonist that acts on the spinal cord to suppress hyperactive reflexes. Used for spasticity in [[45dd6d19|multiple sclerosis]] and spinal cord injury.</li><li><b>Cyclobenzaprine:</b> A centrally acting muscle relaxant, structurally related to TCAs. Used for acute muscle spasms from musculoskeletal conditions. Has significant anticholinergic side effects and causes sedation.</li><li><b>Tizanidine:</b> A centrally acting Œ±<sub>2</sub>-adrenergic agonist that inhibits motor neuron activity. Used for spasticity. Can cause hypotension, sedation, and dry mouth.</li><li><b>Dantrolene:</b> Acts directly on skeletal muscle by blocking Ca<sup>2+</sup> release from the sarcoplasmic reticulum (inhibits ryanodine receptor). <u>Used to treat malignant hyperthermia and neuroleptic malignant syndrome</u>.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Differentiate the uses: [[baclofen]] and tizanidine for chronic spasticity (MS, spinal cord injury), cyclobenzaprine for acute muscle strain, and [[dantrolene]] for life-threatening hyperthermic syndromes.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Antispasmodics</b> reduce muscle hyperactivity through diverse mechanisms, ranging from central GABAergic and adrenergic modulation (baclofen, tizanidine) to direct interference with muscle contraction machinery (dantrolene), the latter being crucial for treating hyperthermic emergencies.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
