    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Brain Lesions"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Aphasia</b> is an acquired language disorder resulting from damage to the language centers of the brain, typically in the dominant (usually left) hemisphere. It affects the ability to produce and/or comprehend spoken or written language, and is distinct from dysarthria (a motor speech disorder).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Broca's Aphasia (Expressive):</b> Lesion in the inferior frontal gyrus ([[a3bbace2|Broca's area]]). Characterized by <mark>nonfluent, telegraphic speech</mark> with intact comprehension. Patients are often frustrated by their inability to speak. Mnemonic: <b>B</b>roca's is <b>B</b>roken <b>B</b>oca (mouth).</li><li><b>Wernicke's Aphasia (Receptive):</b> Lesion in the superior temporal gyrus ([[wernicke_area|Wernicke's area]]). Characterized by <mark>fluent but meaningless speech</mark> (word salad) with severely impaired comprehension. Patients are often unaware of their deficit (anosognosia).</li><li><b>Conduction Aphasia:</b> Lesion of the <mark>arcuate fasciculus</mark>, which connects Broca's and Wernicke's areas. Hallmark is poor repetition despite fluent speech and intact comprehension.</li><li><b>Global Aphasia:</b> Large lesion affecting both Broca's and Wernicke's areas, typically from a large [[143bb23d|MCA stroke]]. All language functions (fluency, comprehension, repetition) are severely impaired.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The most common cause of aphasia is an ischemic [[c5da3c57|stroke]] in the territory of the left [[143bb23d|Middle Cerebral Artery (MCA)]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Aphasia</b> is a disorder of language, not speech mechanics, with distinct subtypes that can be precisely localized within the dominant cerebral hemisphere: Broca's area for production, Wernicke's area for comprehension, and the arcuate fasciculus for repetition.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Left MCA Stroke] --> B{Aphasia Types}; B --> C[Broca's - Nonfluent, Good Comprehension]; B --> D[Wernicke's - Fluent, Poor Comprehension]; B --> E[Conduction - Poor Repetition]; B --> F[Global - All Impaired];"
