  "1a804e11": {
    "title": "Apoptosis",
    "primaryType": "physiology",
    "tags": [
      "Cell Biology",
      "Pathology",
      "Physiology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Cellular Injury"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Apoptosis</b> is a form of programmed cell death that is a highly regulated and controlled process, essential for normal tissue turnover, embryonic development, and removal of damaged or infected cells. In the context of neurology, it is the primary mechanism of neuronal death in many neurodegenerative diseases.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Key Features:</b> Characterized by cell shrinkage, chromatin condensation (pyknosis), membrane blebbing, and formation of apoptotic bodies, which are then phagocytosed. It is an ATP-dependent process and does <u>not</u> induce inflammation.</li><li><b>Pathways:</b><br> - <b>Intrinsic (Mitochondrial):</b> Activated by cellular stress (e.g., DNA damage, misfolded proteins). Regulated by the Bcl-2 family of proteins. Pro-apoptotic proteins (Bax, Bak) create pores in the mitochondrial membrane, releasing cytochrome c, which activates caspases.<br> - <b>Extrinsic (Death Receptor):</b> Activated by external ligands (e.g., FasL, TNF-Œ±) binding to death receptors on the cell surface, directly activating caspases.</li><li><b>Caspases:</b> The central executioners of apoptosis are a family of cysteine proteases called caspases, which orchestrate the degradation of cellular components.</li><li><b>Neurologic Relevance:</b> Apoptosis of lower motor neurons is a key feature of [[4ed629f9|Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS)]]. It is also the mechanism of neuronal loss in [[ffd7e743|Huntington disease]] and [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Contrast apoptosis with necrosis. Necrosis is uncontrolled cell death due to injury, causing cell swelling, membrane rupture, and inflammation. Apoptosis is clean, programmed, and non-inflammatory.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Apoptosis</b> is the cell's intrinsic suicide program, executed by caspases, which neatly packages the cell for disposal without triggering an inflammatory response; its dysregulation is a central theme in both cancer (too little apoptosis) and neurodegeneration (too much apoptosis).</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A{Cellular Stress} --> B(Intrinsic Pathway); B --> C(Mitochondria); C --Cytochrome c--> D; E{Death Ligands} --> F(Extrinsic Pathway); F --> D(Caspase Activation); D --> G(Execution Phase); G --> H(Apoptotic Body Formation);"
    },
    "connections": [
