  "c1f67280": {
    "title": "Apraclonidine",
    "primaryType": "drug",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Autonomic",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Glaucoma Therapy"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Apraclonidine</b> is an <i>Œ±<sub>2</sub>-adrenergic agonist</i> used topically in ophthalmology to lower intraocular pressure (IOP), primarily for the short-term treatment of [[3ce6c035|glaucoma]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> As a selective Œ±<sub>2</sub>-agonist, it acts on presynaptic Œ±<sub>2</sub> receptors in the ciliary body to <mark>decrease aqueous humor synthesis</mark>. It also has some minor effect on increasing uveoscleral outflow.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Used to lower IOP in patients with [[5ea7b741|open-angle glaucoma]]. It is particularly useful for preventing post-surgical IOP spikes. Its use is often limited to the short term due to tachyphylaxis (diminishing response).</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Ocular side effects include blurry vision, ocular hyperemia (redness), foreign body sensation, and ocular allergic reactions. Systemic side effects are rare but can include dry mouth and fatigue.</li><li><b>Comparison:</b> Similar to [[brimonidine]], another Œ±<sub>2</sub>-agonist used for glaucoma, but apraclonidine has a higher rate of tachyphylaxis and allergic reactions.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember that Œ±<sub>2</sub>-agonists (like apraclonidine and clonidine) work by reducing sympathetic outflow. In the eye, this translates to decreased production of aqueous humor.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Apraclonidine</b> lowers intraocular pressure by acting as a 'brake' on aqueous humor production, stimulating Œ±<sub>2</sub>-receptors in the ciliary body to reduce fluid synthesis, making it a useful agent for short-term management of glaucoma.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Apraclonidine] --> B(Stimulates Œ±2 Receptors in Ciliary Body); B --> C(‚Üì Norepinephrine Release); C --> D(‚Üì Aqueous Humor Synthesis); D --> E(‚Üì Intraocular Pressure);"
    },
    "connections": [
