  "eb32eb82": {
    "title": "Gait Apraxia",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Geriatrics",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Gait Disorders"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Gait apraxia</b> is a high-level gait disorder characterized by the inability to properly coordinate the motor sequences for walking, despite having normal motor, sensory, and cerebellar function. It is often described as a <mark>\"magnetic gait,\"</mark> where the feet appear stuck to the floor.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Patients have difficulty initiating walking. The gait is wide-based, shuffling, and slow, with the feet barely leaving the ground. Turning is particularly difficult and requires multiple small steps.</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> It is considered a disorder of the frontal lobes or their connections, disrupting the cortical control of locomotion.</li><li><b>Classic Association:</b> Gait apraxia is one of the three cardinal signs of <mark>[[7c59030e|Normal Pressure Hydrocephalus (NPH)]]</mark>.</li><li><b>NPH Triad:</b> The classic triad is \"<b>W</b>obbly, <b>W</b>acky, and <b>W</b>et\":<br>1. <b>Wobbly:</b> Gait apraxia.<br>2. <b>Wacky:</b> Cognitive dysfunction/dementia.<br>3. <b>Wet:</b> Urinary incontinence.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The description of a 'magnetic' or 'feet stuck to the floor' gait in an elderly patient, especially when combined with cognitive changes and urinary incontinence, is a classic vignette for [[7c59030e|Normal Pressure Hydrocephalus]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Gait apraxia</b> is a 'brain' problem, not a 'leg' problem; it represents a failure of the frontal lobe's motor programming for walking, famously manifesting as the 'magnetic' gait of [[7c59030e|Normal Pressure Hydrocephalus]].</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
