  "d595b0bf": {
    "title": "Aqueous Humor Pathway",
    "primaryType": "physiology",
    "tags": [
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Anatomy",
      "Physiology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Physiology"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Aqueous Humor Pathway</b> describes the continuous production, circulation, and drainage of aqueous humor, the clear fluid that fills the anterior and posterior chambers of the eye. The balance between production and drainage determines the intraocular pressure (IOP).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Production:</b> Aqueous humor is produced by the <mark>nonpigmented epithelium of the ciliary body</mark>. This process is decreased by Œ≤-blockers, Œ±<sub>2</sub>-agonists, and carbonic anhydrase inhibitors.</li><li><b>Circulation:</b> Fluid flows from the posterior chamber, through the pupil, into the anterior chamber.</li><li><b>Drainage Pathways:</b><br>1. <b>Trabecular Outflow (~90%):</b> Fluid drains through the trabecular meshwork, into the Canal of Schlemm, and then into the episcleral vasculature. This pathway is enhanced by muscarinic agonists (e.g., pilocarpine).<br>2. <b>Uveoscleral Outflow (~10%):</b> Fluid drains through the ciliary muscle and into the uveal and scleral tissues. This pathway is enhanced by prostaglandin analogs (e.g., latanoprost).</li><li><b>Clinical Relevance:</b> Imbalance in this pathway leads to [[3ce6c035|glaucoma]]. [[5ea7b741|Open-angle glaucoma]] involves increased resistance in the trabecular meshwork, while [[9c80344d|angle-closure glaucoma]] involves physical obstruction of the angle.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Understand how different glaucoma medications target this pathway. Prostaglandins increase uveoscleral outflow, while Œ≤-blockers and acetazolamide decrease production.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Aqueous Humor Pathway</b> is a dynamic circulatory system within the eye's anterior segment, where a delicate equilibrium between ciliary body production and dual-route (trabecular and uveoscleral) drainage is essential for maintaining normal intraocular pressure.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Ciliary Body Epithelium] --Produces--> B(Aqueous Humor); B --> C(Posterior Chamber); C --> D(Anterior Chamber); D --> E{Drainage}; E --> F[Trabecular Outflow (90%)]; F --> G[Canal of Schlemm]; E --> H[Uveoscleral Outflow (10%)];"
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_dysregulated_in",
        "to": "3ce6c035"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_targeted_by",
        "to": "glaucoma_drugs"
      }
    ]
  }
}
