    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Arachnoid granulations</b> (or arachnoid villi) are microscopic protrusions of the [[46e279b9|arachnoid mater]] through the dura mater into the superior sagittal sinus and other [[21f1c955|dural venous sinuses]], functioning as one-way valves for the drainage of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) from the subarachnoid space into the venous circulation.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Function:</b> The primary site for <mark>CSF reabsorption</mark> into the bloodstream.</li><li><b>Mechanism:</b> CSF flows from the subarachnoid space into the venous sinus down a pressure gradient. The structure acts as a one-way valve, preventing venous blood from entering the subarachnoid space.</li><li><b>Location:</b> Most numerous along the <mark>superior sagittal sinus</mark>.</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> Impaired function or obstruction of arachnoid granulations (e.g., from scarring after meningitis or subarachnoid hemorrhage) can lead to <mark>[[aa4115c7|communicating hydrocephalus]]</mark>.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember that CSF is produced by the choroid plexus and reabsorbed by the arachnoid granulations. A problem with reabsorption (communicating hydrocephalus) is distinct from a blockage of flow within the ventricles (non-communicating hydrocephalus).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Arachnoid granulations</b> are the critical drainage ports for cerebrospinal fluid, acting as sophisticated one-way valves that allow CSF to exit the subarachnoid space and return to the venous system, thereby maintaining intracranial pressure homeostasis.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Choroid Plexus] --Produces--> B(CSF); B --> C(Ventricular System); C --> D(Subarachnoid Space); D --> E(Arachnoid Granulations); E --Reabsorption--> F[Dural Venous Sinuses];"
