  "5dd343d3": {
    "title": "Area Postrema",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroanatomy",
      "Physiology",
      "Pharmacology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Brainstem"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Area Postrema</b> is a highly vascularized structure in the medulla oblongata, located on the floor of the fourth ventricle, that functions as the <mark>chemoreceptor trigger zone (CTZ)</mark> for vomiting. It is one of the circumventricular organs, meaning it lacks a complete [[dd47b9cc|blood-brain barrier]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Location:</b> Dorsal surface of the medulla oblongata at the caudal end of the fourth ventricle.</li><li><b>Function:</b> Detects emetogenic toxins in the blood and CSF and sends signals to the [[74b651ab|vomiting center]] (nucleus tractus solitarius) to induce emesis (vomiting).</li><li><b>Blood-Brain Barrier:</b> Its fenestrated capillaries allow it to directly sample the chemical composition of the blood.</li><li><b>Receptors:</b> Rich in various receptors, including dopamine D<sub>2</sub>, serotonin 5-HT<sub>3</sub>, and neurokinin-1 (NK-1) receptors.</li><li><b>Clinical Relevance:</b> This is the site of action for many antiemetic drugs. For example, [[ondansetron]] is a 5-HT<sub>3</sub> antagonist, and [[metoclopramide]] is a D<sub>2</sub> antagonist. It is also the area stimulated by toxins during chemotherapy, leading to chemotherapy-induced nausea and vomiting.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Area Postrema</b> serves as the brain's chemical surveillance system for the blood; its lack of a blood-brain barrier allows it to detect toxins and trigger the protective reflex of vomiting, making it a key target for antiemetic medications.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Emetogenic Toxins in Blood] --> B(Area Postrema/CTZ); B --> C(Vomiting Center - NTS); C --> D(Vomiting Reflex);"
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_a",
