  "08cb577f": {
    "title": "Argyll Robertson Pupil",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Infectious Disease",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Cranial Nerves"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Argyll Robertson Pupil</b> is a specific type of pupillary abnormality characterized by bilateral small pupils that constrict when the patient focuses on a near object (accommodation reflex) but do <u>not</u> constrict when exposed to bright light (light reflex). This phenomenon is known as <mark>light-near dissociation</mark>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Classic Mnemonic:</b> Often called the \"prostitute's pupil\" because it \"accommodates but does not react.\"</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> The lesion is thought to be in the <mark>pretectal nucleus</mark> in the superior colliculus of the midbrain, which interrupts the afferent limb of the pupillary light reflex pathway before it reaches the Edinger-Westphal nuclei bilaterally. The pathway for accommodation, which is more complex and involves the cerebral cortex, is spared.</li><li><b>Classic Association:</b> It is a highly specific sign of late-stage, or tertiary, <mark>neurosyphilis</mark>, particularly [[71daebd6|tabes dorsalis]].</li><li><b>Other Causes:</b> While classic for syphilis, it can also be seen in other conditions causing midbrain lesions, such as diabetes mellitus or Parinaud syndrome.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient with ataxia, a positive Romberg sign, and pupils that accommodate but don't react to light is a classic presentation of [[71daebd6|tabes dorsalis]] due to neurosyphilis.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Argyll Robertson Pupil</b> is a pathognomonic sign of neurosyphilis, representing a selective lesion in the midbrain that disconnects the pupillary light reflex pathway while preserving the separate, cortically-driven accommodation pathway, resulting in the classic light-near dissociation.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Light] --> B(Optic Nerve); B --> C(Pretectal Nucleus); C --x Lesion; C --x D(Edinger-Westphal Nucleus); E[Near Object] --> F(Visual Cortex); F --> G(Accommodation Pathway); G --> D; D --> H(Pupillary Constriction);"
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_a_sign_of",
        "to": "neurosyphilis"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_a_sign_of",
        "to": "71daebd6"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_caused_by_lesion_in",
        "to": "pretectal_nucleus"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_an_example_of",
        "to": "light_near_dissociation"
      }
    ]
  },
  "09db7b12": {
    "title": "Aspirin",
    "primaryType": "drug",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Cardiology",
      "Neurology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Stroke Therapy"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Aspirin</b> (acetylsalicylic acid) is a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) that irreversibly inhibits cyclooxygenase (COX) enzymes, primarily used at low doses for its antiplatelet effects in the prevention of cardiovascular and cerebrovascular events.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> <u>Irreversibly</u> acetylates and inhibits both COX-1 and COX-2. Its antiplatelet effect is due to inhibition of COX-1 in platelets, which blocks the synthesis of <mark>Thromboxane A<sub>2</sub> (TXA<sub>2</sub>)</mark>, a potent promoter of platelet aggregation.</li><li><b>Clinical Use (Neurology):</b> Used for secondary prevention of [[c5da3c57|ischemic stroke]] and [[623ba776|transient ischemic attacks (TIAs)]]. It is a cornerstone of antiplatelet therapy.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> GI distress (gastritis, ulcers), bleeding, tinnitus (a sign of toxicity), and Reye syndrome in children with viral illness.</li><li><b>Reye Syndrome:</b> A rare but severe condition of acute encephalopathy and fatty liver failure in children given aspirin for a viral infection (e.g., influenza, varicella). <u>Aspirin is contraindicated in children</u> for this reason (except in Kawasaki disease).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The irreversibility of aspirin's effect on platelets is key. Since platelets lack a nucleus, they cannot synthesize new COX enzyme, so the antiplatelet effect lasts for the life of the platelet (~7-10 days).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Aspirin's</b> primary role in stroke prevention stems from its unique ability to <u>irreversibly</u> inhibit platelet COX-1, effectively silencing thromboxane A<sub>2</sub> production for the platelet's entire lifespan and thus reducing the risk of thrombotic occlusion.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Aspirin] --Irreversibly Inhibits--> B(Platelet COX-1); B --x C(Arachidonic Acid -> Thromboxane A2); C --x D(Platelet Aggregation); D --x E(Thrombus Formation);"
    },
    "connections": [
