  "18cff34e": {
    "title": "Astigmatism",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Physiology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Refractive Errors"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Astigmatism</b> is a common refractive error of the eye where vision is blurred or distorted at all distances. It occurs when the cornea or lens has an irregular, non-spherical curvature, causing light rays to focus at multiple points rather than a single point on the retina.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> The cornea, which should be shaped like a sphere, is instead shaped more like a football (toric). This causes light entering the eye to have different focal points in different planes (e.g., vertical vs. horizontal).</li><li><b>Symptoms:</b> Blurred or distorted vision, eye strain, and headaches.</li><li><b>Diagnosis:</b> Diagnosed during a standard eye exam using a phoropter and keratometer.</li><li><b>Correction:</b> Corrected with eyeglasses or contact lenses that have a <mark>cylindrical lens</mark> to compensate for the irregular curvature. It can also be corrected with refractive surgery (e.g., LASIK).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Differentiate from other refractive errors: [[myopia|myopia]] (nearsightedness) and [[hyperopia|hyperopia]] (farsightedness) are caused by the length of the eyeball relative to its focusing power, while astigmatism is caused by an irregularly shaped cornea or lens.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Astigmatism</b> is a refractive error caused by an asymmetrically shaped cornea or lens, which acts like a warped mirror, scattering light to multiple focal points and resulting in blurred vision that requires a cylindrical lens for correction.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_a_type_of",
        "to": "refractive_error"
      },
      {
        "type": "differentiated_from",
        "to": "myopia"
      },
      {
        "type": "differentiated_from",
        "to": "hyperopia"
      }
    ]
  },
  "8192f595": {
    "title": "Astrocytes",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroanatomy",
      "Histology",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Glial Cells"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Astrocytes</b> are the most abundant type of glial cell in the central nervous system. These star-shaped cells perform a wide variety of essential supportive and homeostatic functions for neurons, and are the origin of the most common primary brain tumor in adults, [[b6bbd0bc|glioblastoma]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Functions:</b> Physical support for neurons, repair (gliosis/scar formation), component of the [[dd47b9cc|blood-brain barrier]] (via foot processes), removal of excess neurotransmitters (especially glutamate), and maintenance of the ionic environment.</li><li><b>Histological Marker:</b> They are identified by their expression of <mark>Glial Fibrillary Acidic Protein (GFAP)</mark>, an intermediate filament protein.</li><li><b>Reactive Gliosis:</b> In response to CNS injury (e.g., stroke, trauma), astrocytes proliferate and hypertrophy to form a <mark>glial scar</mark>, which walls off the damaged area but can also impede axonal regeneration.</li><li><b>Tumor Origin:</b> Astrocytes are the cell of origin for astrocytomas, including the highly malignant [[b6bbd0bc|glioblastoma]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember GFAP as the key marker for astrocytes and astrocytic tumors. The formation of a glial scar by astrocytes is the CNS equivalent of fibrosis in other tissues.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Astrocytes</b> are the indispensable 'housekeepers' of the CNS, providing structural, metabolic, and homeostatic support to neurons, forming the blood-brain barrier, and orchestrating the glial scar response to injury, but they can also give rise to the most aggressive brain tumors.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Astrocyte]; A --> B(Physical Support); A --> C(Blood-Brain Barrier); A --> D(Neurotransmitter Uptake); A --> E(Ion Buffering); A --> F(Repair/Gliosis); A --Neoplastic Transformation--> G(Astrocytoma/Glioblastoma);"
    },
    "connections": [
