  "9767fd6b": {
    "title": "Ataxia",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Physical Exam",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Movement Disorders"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Ataxia</b> is a neurological sign consisting of a lack of voluntary coordination of muscle movements, leading to a clumsy, unsteady gait and impaired balance. It can be caused by damage to the cerebellum, the vestibular system, or sensory pathways.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Cerebellar Ataxia:</b> Caused by damage to the cerebellum. <br> - <b>Truncal Ataxia:</b> Affects the midline, causing an unsteady, wide-based ('drunken sailor') gait. Associated with lesions of the cerebellar vermis.<br> - <b>Limb Ataxia:</b> Affects the extremities, causing dysmetria (overshooting/undershooting targets) and intention tremor. Associated with lesions of the cerebellar hemispheres.</li><li><b>Sensory Ataxia:</b> Caused by loss of proprioception, typically from damage to the [[e7f5cbbe|dorsal columns]] of the spinal cord or peripheral nerves. Patients have a positive [[47a0f3d1|Romberg sign]] (worsening of balance with eyes closed) and a stomping gait. Seen in [[71daebd6|tabes dorsalis]] and [[6f5bea90|subacute combined degeneration]].</li><li><b>Vestibular Ataxia:</b> Caused by dysfunction of the vestibular system. Associated with vertigo, nystagmus, and nausea.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Differentiating the type of ataxia is key. A positive [[47a0f3d1|Romberg sign]] points to a sensory (dorsal column) cause, not a cerebellar cause. Patients with cerebellar ataxia are unsteady with their eyes open or closed.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Ataxia</b> is a sign of discoordination that can be localized by its characteristics: truncal and limb incoordination points to the cerebellum, a positive Romberg sign points to sensory loss in the dorsal columns, and associated vertigo points to the vestibular system.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_a_sign_of",
        "to": "cerebellar_lesion"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_a_sign_of",
        "to": "dorsal_column_lesion"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_a_sign_of",
        "to": "vestibular_dysfunction"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_a_symptom_of",
        "to": "71daebd6"
      }
    ]
  },
  "19272e70": {
    "title": "Athetosis",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Movement Disorders",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Movement Disorders"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Athetosis</b> is a type of involuntary movement disorder characterized by slow, writhing, snake-like movements, particularly affecting the distal extremities (fingers and hands). It is a symptom of damage to the [[ed462927|basal ganglia]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Description:</b> Slow, twisting, and writhing movements that are continuous and non-rhythmic. It is often described as being 'snake-like.'</li><li><b>Lesion Location:</b> Caused by lesions in the [[ed462927|basal ganglia]], particularly the striatum (caudate and putamen).</li><li><b>Classic Association:</b> Athetosis is a characteristic feature of [[ffd7e743|Huntington disease]], where it often co-occurs with chorea (termed choreoathetosis).</li><li><b>Other Causes:</b> Can also be seen in conditions like cerebral palsy.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> When you see a description of slow, writhing, 'snake-like' movements of the fingers in a patient with other signs of a basal ganglia disorder (like chorea or dementia), think of athetosis, especially in the context of [[ffd7e743|Huntington disease]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Athetosis</b> is a specific and visually distinct sign of basal ganglia dysfunction, representing a failure of motor control that manifests as slow, ceaseless, writhing movements, most classically seen in [[ffd7e743|Huntington disease]].</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_a_symptom_of",
        "to": "ffd7e743"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_caused_by_lesion_in",
        "to": "ed462927"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_a_type_of",
