  "ed7a236f": {
    "title": "Atonic Seizures",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Pediatrics",
      "Epilepsy",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Seizures"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Atonic seizures</b>, also known as \"drop attacks\" or \"drop seizures,\" are a type of generalized seizure characterized by a sudden loss of muscle tone, causing the individual to collapse to the ground. The loss of consciousness is typically very brief.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> A sudden, complete loss of postural muscle tone lasting 1-2 seconds. This can cause the head to drop, the jaw to slacken, or the entire body to fall limply to the floor.</li><li><b>Risk of Injury:</b> There is a high risk of head and facial injuries from the sudden falls. Patients may need to wear protective helmets.</li><li><b>Associated Syndromes:</b> While they can occur in various epilepsy syndromes, atonic seizures are a hallmark feature of <mark>Lennox-Gastaut syndrome</mark>, a severe form of childhood epilepsy.</li><li><b>EEG Findings:</b> The EEG may show brief, generalized spike-and-wave discharges followed by diffuse slow waves.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A vignette describing a child with developmental delay who has multiple seizure types, including sudden falls leading to injury, is highly suggestive of Lennox-Gastaut syndrome, with atonic seizures being a key component.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Atonic seizures</b> are dramatic 'drop attacks' caused by a sudden, global loss of muscle tone, posing a significant risk of injury and often signaling a severe underlying epilepsy syndrome like Lennox-Gastaut.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_a_type_of",
        "to": "64c08e92"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_a_feature_of",
        "to": "lennox_gastaut_syndrome"
      }
    ]
  },
  "52194edb": {
    "title": "Atracurium",
    "primaryType": "drug",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Anesthesiology",
      "Neurology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Neuromuscular Blockers"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Atracurium</b> is a non-depolarizing <i>neuromuscular blocking agent</i> used in anesthesia to induce skeletal muscle relaxation and paralysis, facilitating endotracheal intubation and surgical procedures.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Acts as a competitive antagonist at nicotinic acetylcholine receptors at the neuromuscular junction, preventing [[6a005559|acetylcholine]] from binding and causing muscle contraction.</li><li><b>Metabolism:</b> Undergoes <mark>Hoffmann elimination</mark>, a spontaneous, non-enzymatic degradation at physiological pH and temperature. This makes its metabolism independent of liver or kidney function.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Ideal for patients with <mark>renal or hepatic failure</mark> because its elimination does not depend on these organs.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Can cause histamine release, leading to hypotension, flushing, and bronchoconstriction. Its metabolite, laudanosine, can lower the seizure threshold, but this is rarely clinically significant.</li><li><b>Reversal:</b> The neuromuscular blockade can be reversed by [[acetylcholinesterase_inhibitors|acetylcholinesterase inhibitors]] (e.g., neostigmine), which increase the concentration of acetylcholine in the synaptic cleft to outcompete the blocker.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The key feature of atracurium (and its stereoisomer, cisatracurium) is its Hoffmann elimination, making it the neuromuscular blocker of choice for patients with organ dysfunction.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Atracurium</b> is a non-depolarizing neuromuscular blocker distinguished by its unique Hoffmann elimination pathway, a spontaneous chemical breakdown that makes it a safe and predictable choice for inducing paralysis in patients with kidney or liver disease.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Atracurium] --Competitively Antagonizes--> B(Nicotinic ACh Receptors); B --x C(ACh Binding); C --x D(Muscle Contraction); A --Hoffmann Elimination--> E(Inactive Metabolites);"
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_a_type_of",
        "to": "nondepolarizing_neuromuscular_blocker"
      },
      {
        "type": "undergoes",
        "to": "hoffmann_elimination"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_reversed_by",
        "to": "acetylcholinesterase_inhibitors"
