    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Atrophy</b> is a cellular adaptation characterized by a decrease in the size of a cell, organ, or tissue after it has reached its normal mature size. It results from a decrease in cell substance and can be either physiologic or pathologic.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism:</b> Atrophy occurs via a decrease in protein synthesis and an increase in protein degradation. The main pathway for protein degradation is the <mark>ubiquitin-proteasome pathway</mark>. It can also involve autophagy, where the cell digests its own components.</li><li><b>Causes:</b> Common causes include disuse, denervation, loss of endocrine stimulation, inadequate nutrition, and ischemia.</li><li><b>Neurologic Relevance (Denervation Atrophy):</b> When a muscle loses its nerve supply (denervation), it undergoes rapid and profound atrophy. This is a key sign of a <mark>lower motor neuron (LMN) lesion</mark>.</li><li><b>UMN vs. LMN Lesions:</b> Significant muscle atrophy is a hallmark of LMN lesions (e.g., polio, [[4ed629f9|ALS]], peripheral nerve injury). In contrast, upper motor neuron (UMN) lesions cause only mild disuse atrophy.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> In a clinical vignette, the presence of marked muscle wasting (atrophy) and fasciculations strongly points towards an LMN component of a disease process.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Atrophy</b> is a reduction in cell size and substance, most often driven by the ubiquitin-proteasome pathway. In neurology, denervation atrophy is a critical sign that localizes a lesion to the lower motor neuron, distinguishing it from upper motor neuron pathology.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
