    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Auditory anatomy and physiology</b> describes the structures and mechanisms by which sound waves are collected, transmitted, transduced into neural signals, and processed by the brain to produce the sensation of hearing.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Outer Ear:</b> The pinna and external auditory canal collect sound waves and funnel them to the tympanic membrane (eardrum).</li><li><b>Middle Ear:</b> An air-filled cavity containing the ossicles (malleus, incus, stapes). The ossicles amplify the vibrations from the tympanic membrane and transmit them to the oval window of the inner ear.</li><li><b>Inner Ear:</b> The [[001c359f|cochlea]], a fluid-filled, snail-shaped structure, contains the organ of Corti. Vibrations from the stapes create pressure waves in the cochlear fluid.</li><li><b>Transduction:</b> These pressure waves cause the basilar membrane to vibrate at specific locations depending on the frequency (tonotopy). High frequencies vibrate the base, low frequencies vibrate the apex. This vibration bends the stereocilia of hair cells in the organ of Corti, opening ion channels and generating a neural signal.</li><li><b>Neural Pathway:</b> The signal travels from the hair cells via the cochlear nerve (part of CN VIII) to the cochlear nuclei in the brainstem, then through a complex pathway (superior olive, lateral lemniscus, inferior colliculus, medial geniculate nucleus of the thalamus) to the [[d24b6af6|auditory cortex]] in the temporal lobe.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The auditory system is a remarkable transducer, converting mechanical energy (sound waves) into mechanical vibration (ossicles), then into hydraulic waves (cochlear fluid), and finally into electrical signals (hair cells) that the brain interprets as sound.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Sound Waves] --> B(Outer Ear); B --> C(Tympanic Membrane); C --> D(Middle Ear Ossicles); D --> E(Oval Window); E --> F(Cochlear Fluid); F --> G(Basilar Membrane Vibration); G --> H(Hair Cell Transduction); H --> I(CN VIII); I --> J(Brain); "
