      "Autonomic Nervous System"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Autonomic Nervous System (ANS)</b> is the division of the peripheral nervous system that controls involuntary bodily functions, such as heart rate, digestion, respiratory rate, and pupillary response. It is subdivided into the sympathetic, parasympathetic, and enteric systems.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Sympathetic Division:</b> Mediates the \"fight or flight\" response. Preganglionic neurons are short and release [[6a005559|acetylcholine]] onto nicotinic receptors in the paravertebral ganglia. Postganglionic neurons are long and primarily release norepinephrine onto adrenergic receptors.</li><li><b>Parasympathetic Division:</b> Mediates the \"rest and digest\" response. Preganglionic neurons are long and release [[6a005559|acetylcholine]] onto nicotinic receptors in ganglia near or within target organs. Postganglionic neurons are short and release [[6a005559|acetylcholine]] onto muscarinic receptors.</li><li><b>CNS Control:</b> The ANS is regulated by higher centers in the CNS, including the [[89e86633|hypothalamus]] and the [[73ace357|limbic system]], which modulate autonomic outflow in response to emotional and environmental stimuli.</li><li><b>Clinical Relevance:</b> Autonomic dysregulation is a feature of many neurological disorders, including [[ed52e40b|Guillain-Barr√© syndrome]] (acute inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy), which can cause life-threatening cardiac irregularities and blood pressure instability.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Understand the neurotransmitter/receptor pairings: All preganglionic neurons use ACh (nicotinic). Parasympathetic postganglionic neurons use ACh (muscarinic). Most sympathetic postganglionic neurons use norepinephrine (adrenergic), with the key exception being sweat glands (ACh, muscarinic).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Autonomic Nervous System</b> maintains homeostasis through a balance of its sympathetic ('gas pedal') and parasympathetic ('brake pedal') divisions, utilizing a two-neuron chain with distinct neurotransmitters and receptor targets to exert involuntary control over virtually every organ system.</p>",
