    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Trauma"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Axonal injury</b> refers to damage to the axons of neurons, which can occur from trauma, ischemia, or neurodegenerative processes. The neuronal response to injury and the potential for regeneration depend on whether the injury is in the central or peripheral nervous system.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Wallerian Degeneration:</b> The process of degeneration of the axon <u>distal</u> to the site of injury. The axon disintegrates and its myelin sheath breaks down, cleared by Schwann cells (PNS) or microglia (CNS).</li><li><b>Axonal Reaction (Central Chromatolysis):</b> Changes occurring in the neuronal cell body <u>proximal</u> to the injury. The cell body swells, the nucleus is displaced to the periphery, and Nissl bodies disperse. This reflects an increase in protein synthesis for repair.</li><li><b>Diffuse Axonal Injury (DAI):</b> A severe form of traumatic brain injury caused by shearing forces from rapid acceleration/deceleration. It involves widespread damage to axons in the white matter tracts. MRI shows multiple punctate hemorrhages. Often results in coma or persistent vegetative state.</li><li><b>Regeneration:</b> Axonal regeneration is limited in the CNS due to inhibitory factors from oligodendrocytes and glial scar formation by astrocytes. Regeneration is more successful in the PNS, guided by the remaining Schwann cells and endoneurial tube.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the key difference in response to injury: Wallerian degeneration occurs distal to the cut, while axonal reaction (chromatolysis) occurs in the proximal cell body.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Axonal injury</b> triggers a cascade of degenerative and regenerative processes, with the outcome largely determined by the location; peripheral nerves have a significant capacity for regeneration guided by Schwann cells, whereas central nervous system axons are largely unable to regenerate due to an inhibitory environment.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Axon Injury] --> B(Proximal Segment); B --> C(Axonal Reaction/Chromatolysis); A --> D(Distal Segment); D --> E(Wallerian Degeneration);"
    },
