    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Physical Exam",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Spinal Cord"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Babinski reflex</b> (or sign) is the dorsiflexion of the great toe and fanning of the other toes in response to stroking the plantar surface of the foot. While a normal primitive reflex in infants, its presence in an adult is a pathognomonic sign of an <u>upper motor neuron (UMN) lesion</u>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Technique:</b> The sole of the foot is stroked with a blunt object from the heel along the lateral aspect to the ball of the foot.</li><li><b>Normal Response (Adult):</b> Plantar flexion (downward curling) of the toes.</li><li><b>Abnormal Response (Babinski Sign):</b> Extension (dorsiflexion) of the great toe and fanning of the other toes.</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> The sign indicates damage to the corticospinal tract, which normally suppresses this primitive reflex after infancy.</li><li><b>Clinical Significance:</b> A positive Babinski sign is a key physical exam finding that helps differentiate UMN lesions from LMN lesions. It is a sign of <mark>upper motor neuron damage</mark>.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> In an adult, a positive Babinski sign is <u>always</u> abnormal. It points to a lesion anywhere along the corticospinal tract, from the motor cortex down to the spinal cord.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Babinski sign</b> is a clinical indicator of corticospinal tract dysfunction, representing the re-emergence of a primitive reflex that is normally suppressed by mature upper motor neurons; its presence in an adult is a definitive sign of a UMN lesion.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
