  "1ddc3f08": {
    "title": "Baclofen",
    "primaryType": "drug",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Neurology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Skeletal Muscle Relaxants"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Baclofen</b> is a centrally acting skeletal muscle relaxant (antispasmodic) that functions as a GABA<sub>B</sub> receptor agonist, primarily used to treat muscle spasticity.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Acts as an agonist at <mark>GABA<sub>B</sub> receptors</gmark> in the spinal cord. This activation leads to hyperpolarization of motor neurons by increasing K<sup>+</sup> conductance, which reduces the release of excitatory neurotransmitters.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Treatment of spasticity associated with [[45dd6d19|multiple sclerosis]], spinal cord injuries, and [[171ca00b|cerebral palsy]]. It is not typically used for acute muscle spasms from injury.</li><li><b>Administration:</b> Can be administered orally or intrathecally (directly into the CSF) via a pump for severe spasticity.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Sedation, drowsiness, dizziness, and muscle weakness. Abrupt withdrawal of intrathecal baclofen can be life-threatening, causing high fever, rebound spasticity, and seizures.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember that baclofen acts on the '<b>bac</b>k' (spinal cord) at GABA<b><sub>B</sub></b> receptors. Differentiate its use for chronic spasticity from drugs like cyclobenzaprine used for acute muscle spasms.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Baclofen</b> effectively reduces chronic muscle spasticity by mimicking GABA's inhibitory effects at GABA<sub>B</sub> receptors specifically within the spinal cord, thereby dampening the hyperactive reflexes that cause stiffness and spasms.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Baclofen] --> B(Activates GABA-B Receptors in Spinal Cord); B --> C(‚Üë K+ Conductance); C --> D(Hyperpolarization of Motor Neurons); D --> E(‚Üì Spasticity);"
