  "52564aea": {
    "title": "Barbiturates",
    "primaryType": "drug",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Anesthesiology",
      "Neurology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Sedative-Hypnotics"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Barbiturates</b> (e.g., phenobarbital, pentobarbital, thiopental) are a class of sedative-hypnotic drugs that act as central nervous system depressants by enhancing the effects of the neurotransmitter GABA.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Bind to the GABA<sub>A</sub> receptor at a different site than GABA or benzodiazepines. They increase the <mark><u>duration</u></mark> of chloride channel opening. Mnemonic: Barbi<b>durates</b> increase the <b>duration</b>.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Formerly used for anxiety and insomnia but now largely replaced by benzodiazepines due to a worse safety profile. Current uses include: <br> - <b>Anticonvulsant:</b> [[phenobarbital]] for seizures.<br> - <b>Anesthesia:</b> Thiopental for induction of anesthesia.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Significant CNS and respiratory depression, which can be fatal in overdose and is potentiated by alcohol. High potential for dependence and abuse. Induces cytochrome P450 enzymes, leading to numerous drug interactions.</li><li><b>Contraindication:</b> <u>Absolutely contraindicated</u> in patients with porphyria, as they induce Œ¥-ALA synthase.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The key difference from benzodiazepines is the mechanism (duration vs. frequency) and the lack of a ceiling effect on CNS depression, making overdose much more dangerous. There is no specific antidote for barbiturate overdose; treatment is supportive.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Barbiturates</b> are potent CNS depressants that enhance GABAergic inhibition by prolonging the opening of chloride channels, but their narrow therapeutic index and high risk of fatal respiratory depression have relegated them to niche uses like seizure control and anesthesia induction.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Barbiturate] --> B(Binds to GABA-A Receptor); B --> C(‚Üë Duration of Cl- Channel Opening); C --> D(‚Üë Cl- Influx); D --> E(Hyperpolarization of Neuron); E --> F(CNS Depression);"
    },
