  "ed462927": {
    "title": "Basal Ganglia",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroanatomy",
      "Physiology",
      "Movement Disorders",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Basal Ganglia"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Basal Ganglia</b> are a group of subcortical nuclei in the forebrain that are crucial for motor control, particularly in selecting and initiating voluntary movements, while suppressing unwanted movements. They also play a role in procedural learning, habit formation, and emotion.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Components:</b> The main components are the <b>Striatum</b> (caudate nucleus + putamen), <b>Globus Pallidus</b> (internal and external segments), <b>Subthalamic Nucleus</b>, and <b>Substantia Nigra</b> (pars compacta and pars reticulata).</li><li><b>Function:</b> The basal ganglia modulate motor output from the cortex via feedback loops. They do not directly connect to the spinal cord.</li><li><b>Direct Pathway:</b> Facilitates movement. Cortical activation stimulates the striatum, which inhibits the globus pallidus internus (GPi), thereby disinhibiting the [[afc0a64b|thalamus]] and allowing it to excite the motor cortex.</li><li><b>Indirect Pathway:</b> Inhibits movement. This more complex loop ultimately results in stimulation of the GPi, which increases inhibition of the [[afc0a64b|thalamus]], thus suppressing cortical activity.</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> Lesions in the basal ganglia lead to movement disorders. <br> - [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]]: Loss of dopaminergic neurons in the substantia nigra pars compacta leads to bradykinesia and tremor (hypokinetic).<br> - [[ffd7e743|Huntington disease]]: Degeneration of the striatum leads to chorea (hyperkinetic).<br> - Hemiballismus: Lesion of the subthalamic nucleus leads to wild, flinging movements.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Basal Ganglia</b> function as a sophisticated 'gatekeeper' for motor commands, using a balance between a 'go' (direct) pathway and a 'no-go' (indirect) pathway to fine-tune voluntary movement; disruption of this balance is the fundamental cause of movement disorders like Parkinson's and Huntington's disease.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph LR; A[Cortex] --> B(Striatum); B --|Direct Pathway (Go)|--> C(‚Üì GPi/SNr Inhibition); C --> D(‚Üë Thalamic Excitation); D --> A; B --|Indirect Pathway (No-Go)|--> E(‚Üë GPi/SNr Inhibition); E --> F(‚Üì Thalamic Excitation); F --> A;"
    },
