  "361438f2": {
    "title": "Basal Nucleus of Meynert",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroanatomy",
      "Neurology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Brain Nuclei"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Basal Nucleus of Meynert</b> is a group of neurons located in the substantia innominata of the basal forebrain. It is the primary source of cholinergic ([[6a005559|acetylcholine]]) innervation to the entire cerebral cortex, playing a vital role in cognitive functions like memory and attention.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Location:</b> Basal forebrain, part of the substantia innominata.</li><li><b>Neurotransmitter:</b> Synthesizes and releases [[6a005559|acetylcholine (ACh)]].</li><li><b>Projections:</b> Provides widespread cholinergic projections to the neocortex and hippocampus.</li><li><b>Function:</b> Modulates cortical excitability, arousal, attention, and is critical for learning and memory formation.</li><li><b>Clinical Relevance:</b> There is significant degeneration and loss of cholinergic neurons in the Basal Nucleus of Meynert in <mark>[[77ae6148|Alzheimer disease]]</mark>. This loss of cortical ACh is a major contributor to the cognitive and memory deficits seen in the disease.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The degeneration of the Basal Nucleus of Meynert and the resulting cholinergic deficit is a key pathophysiological feature of [[77ae6148|Alzheimer disease]] and is the rationale for using [[acetylcholinesterase_inhibitors|acetylcholinesterase inhibitors]] (e.g., [[47d0372e|donepezil]]) as a symptomatic treatment.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Basal Nucleus of Meynert</b> is the brain's main cholinergic hub for the cortex; its profound degeneration in [[77ae6148|Alzheimer disease]] leads to a cortical acetylcholine deficit that underlies the hallmark cognitive decline of the disease.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Basal Nucleus of Meynert] --ACh Projections--> B(Cerebral Cortex & Hippocampus); B --> C(Arousal, Memory, Attention); A --x Degeneration in Alzheimer's; "
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "produces",
        "to": "6a005559"
      },
      {
        "type": "degenerates_in",
        "to": "77ae6148"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_part_of",
        "to": "basal_forebrain"
      }
    ]
  },
  "253e3efb": {
    "title": "Basal Plate",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Embryology",
      "Neuroscience",
      "Anatomy",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Embryology",
      "Neural Development"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Basal Plate</b> is the ventral part of the neural tube in the developing embryo, which differentiates into <i>motor neurons</i> of the spinal cord and brainstem under the influence of the signaling molecule Sonic Hedgehog (SHH).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Location:</b> Ventral (anterior) region of the developing spinal cord and brainstem.</li><li><b>Function:</b> Gives rise to <u>motor</u> components of the central nervous system, including the anterior horn of the spinal cord and the motor nuclei of the cranial nerves.</li><li><b>Inducing Signal:</b> Development is induced by <mark>Sonic Hedgehog (SHH)</mark>, a signaling molecule secreted by the underlying notochord.</li><li><b>Counterpart:</b> The dorsal counterpart is the [[43be7a6e|Alar Plate]], which develops into sensory neurons under the influence of Bone Morphogenetic Proteins (BMPs).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the simple orientation: <b>Basal = Motor = Ventral</b>, and <b>Alar = Sensory = Dorsal</b>. This fundamental organization persists into the adult CNS.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Basal Plate</b> is the embryonic blueprint for the motor output of the CNS, established by Sonic Hedgehog signaling from the notochord, which sets up the ventral-motor organization of the neural tube that is conserved throughout the nervous system.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Neural Tube] --> B(Alar Plate - Dorsal); A --> C(Basal Plate - Ventral); D[Ectoderm] --BMPs--> B; B --> E[Sensory Neurons]; F[Notochord] --SHH--> C; C --> G[Motor Neurons];"
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_part_of",
        "to": "neural_tube"
      },
      {
        "type": "develops_into",
        "to": "motor_neurons"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_counterpart_to",
        "to": "43be7a6e"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_induced_by",
        "to": "sonic_hedgehog"
