  "e7a90cd9": {
    "title": "Basilar Artery",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroanatomy",
      "Cerebrovascular",
      "Neurology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Cerebral Vasculature"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Basilar Artery</b> is a critical artery at the base of the brain, formed by the union of the two vertebral arteries. It ascends along the anterior surface of the pons and is a key component of the posterior circulation, supplying the brainstem, cerebellum, and occipital lobes.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Formation:</b> Formed by the confluence of the left and right vertebral arteries at the pontomedullary junction.</li><li><b>Branches:</b> Gives rise to the [[3c075343|anterior inferior cerebellar artery (AICA)]], superior cerebellar artery (SCA), and numerous small pontine arteries. It terminates by bifurcating into the two [[b6a2cc31|posterior cerebral arteries (PCAs)]].</li><li><b>Territory Supplied:</b> Brainstem (pons, midbrain), cerebellum, and via its terminal branches (PCAs), the occipital and inferior temporal lobes.</li><li><b>Stroke Syndromes:</b><br> - <b>Basilar Artery Occlusion:</b> Can be catastrophic, leading to <mark>\"locked-in syndrome\"</mark> if the ventral pons is infarcted bilaterally. This causes quadriplegia and mutism, with preserved consciousness and vertical eye movements.<br> - <b>Top of the Basilar Syndrome:</b> Embolic occlusion of the distal basilar artery affects the midbrain, thalamus, and temporal/occipital lobes, causing visual and behavioral disturbances with minimal motor deficits.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A stroke causing quadriplegia but sparing consciousness and vertical eye movements is pathognomonic for basilar artery occlusion leading to locked-in syndrome.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Basilar Artery</b> is the central trunk of the posterior circulation; its occlusion can lead to devastating brainstem strokes, most notably the 'locked-in syndrome,' which severs the brain's motor output while leaving consciousness intact.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Vertebral Arteries] --> B(Basilar Artery); B --> C(Pontine Arteries); B --> D(AICA); B --> E(SCA); B --> F(PCAs);"
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_part_of",
        "to": "posterior_circulation"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_formed_by",
        "to": "vertebral_arteries"
      },
      {
        "type": "occlusion_causes",
        "to": "locked_in_syndrome"
      },
