    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Anesthesiology",
      "Toxicology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Anesthetics"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Benzocaine</b> is an ester-type <i>local anesthetic</i> used topically to numb surfaces such as the skin, mouth, and throat. It works by blocking voltage-gated sodium channels in nerve membranes, thereby preventing the propagation of action potentials.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Blocks voltage-gated Na<sup>+</sup> channels, preventing nerve depolarization.</li><li><b>Class:</b> Ester local anesthetic. Patients with allergies to esters (e.g., procaine) may also react to benzocaine.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Commonly found in over-the-counter products for teething pain, sore throats (sprays), and sunburn relief. Used in medical settings as a topical anesthetic for procedures like endoscopy.</li><li><b>Adverse Effect:</b> A well-known cause of acquired <mark>methemoglobinemia</mark>, especially in infants and young children.</li><li><b>Methemoglobinemia:</b> Benzocaine oxidizes the iron in hemoglobin from the ferrous (Fe<sup>2+</sup>) to the ferric (Fe<sup>3+</sup>) state. Methemoglobin cannot bind oxygen, leading to functional anemia and cyanosis that does not improve with supplemental oxygen. Blood appears 'chocolate brown'. Treated with methylene blue.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A vignette describing a patient who develops cyanosis and shortness of breath shortly after an endoscopic procedure (where a topical anesthetic spray was used) should immediately raise suspicion for benzocaine-induced methemoglobinemia.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Benzocaine</b> is a widely used topical anesthetic that carries the rare but life-threatening risk of inducing methemoglobinemia, a condition where hemoglobin's iron is oxidized, rendering it unable to transport oxygen and causing a characteristic 'chocolate brown' blood appearance and cyanosis.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
