      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Psychiatry",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Anxiolytics"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Benzodiazepines</b> are a class of psychoactive drugs that act as positive allosteric modulators of the GABA<sub>A</sub> receptor, resulting in sedative, hypnotic, anxiolytic, anticonvulsant, and muscle relaxant properties.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Bind to an allosteric site on the GABA<sub>A</sub> receptor, increasing the <mark><u>frequency</u></mark> of chloride channel opening in response to GABA. Mnemonic: <b>Fre</b>nzodiazepines increase <b>fre</b>quency.</li><li><b>Clinical Uses:</b> Anxiety disorders, panic attacks, status epilepticus (lorazepam, diazepam), alcohol withdrawal, insomnia, and procedural sedation/anesthesia (midazolam).</li><li><b>Pharmacokinetics:</b> Classified by duration of action. Short-acting (e.g., [[083094db|alprazolam]], midazolam) have higher abuse potential. Long-acting (e.g., diazepam, chlordiazepoxide) are preferred for alcohol withdrawal. Those not metabolized by the liver (<b>O</b>xazepam, <b>T</b>emazepam, <b>L</b>orazepam - 'Outside The Liver') are safer in patients with hepatic dysfunction.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Sedation, dependence, tolerance, withdrawal symptoms. Additive CNS depression with other depressants like alcohol and barbiturates.</li><li><b>Antidote:</b> Overdose can be treated with <mark>flumazenil</mark>, a competitive antagonist at the benzodiazepine binding site on the GABA<sub>A</sub> receptor.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Differentiate from [[52564aea|barbiturates]], which increase the <u>duration</u> of channel opening and have a higher risk of fatal respiratory depression.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Benzodiazepines</b> are versatile CNS depressants that enhance GABA's inhibitory effects by increasing the frequency of chloride channel opening, but their use is tempered by the significant risks of dependence and additive depression with other substances.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Benzodiazepine] --> B(Binds to GABA-A Receptor); B --> C(‚Üë Frequency of Cl- Channel Opening); C --> D(‚Üë Cl- Influx); D --> E(Hyperpolarization of Neuron); E --> F(CNS Depression/Anxiolysis);"
    },
