      "Parkinson Disease Therapy"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Benztropine</b> is a centrally acting <i>antimuscarinic (anticholinergic) drug</i> used primarily to treat the symptoms of [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]] and to manage extrapyramidal side effects (EPS) caused by antipsychotic medications.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Acts as a competitive antagonist at central muscarinic receptors, helping to restore the dopaminergic-cholinergic balance in the [[ed462927|basal ganglia]] that is disrupted in Parkinson's disease.</li><li><b>Clinical Use (Parkinson's):</b> Primarily effective for treating <mark>tremor and rigidity</mark>. It has little effect on bradykinesia. Mnemonic: '<b>Tri</b> to <b>Park</b> my Mercedes-<b>Benz</b>' (<b>Tri</b>hexyphenidyl and <b>Benz</b>tropine for <b>Park</b>inson's).</li><li><b>Clinical Use (EPS):</b> Effective for treating <mark>acute dystonia</mark> and drug-induced parkinsonism caused by dopamine antagonists (antipsychotics).</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Classic anticholinergic side effects: dry mouth, blurred vision, constipation, urinary retention, tachycardia, and confusion/delirium, especially in the elderly.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Benztropine is the go-to drug for treating a patient who develops an acute dystonic reaction (e.g., torticollis, oculogyric crisis) after starting an antipsychotic like haloperidol.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Benztropine</b> combats the motor symptoms of Parkinson's and antipsychotic side effects by blocking central acetylcholine activity, thereby counteracting the relative cholinergic overactivity that results from dopamine deficiency or blockade in the basal ganglia.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
