  "f36cfe18": {
    "title": "Biceps Reflex",
    "primaryType": "physiology",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Physical Exam",
      "Physiology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Spinal Cord"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Biceps reflex</b> is a deep tendon reflex that causes flexion of the elbow when the biceps brachii tendon is tapped. It is used to test the integrity of the <mark>C5 and C6</mark> spinal nerve roots and the musculocutaneous nerve.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Nerve Roots:</b> Primarily tests the <b>C5</b> nerve root, with a contribution from C6. Mnemonic: C<b>5</b>, 6, pick up sticks.</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> Tapping the biceps tendon stretches the muscle spindle in the biceps muscle. The afferent signal travels via the musculocutaneous nerve to the C5/C6 spinal cord segments. It synapses with a motor neuron, and the efferent signal returns via the musculocutaneous nerve to cause contraction of the biceps muscle and elbow flexion.</li><li><b>Diminished/Absent Reflex:</b> Suggests a lower motor neuron lesion, such as a herniated disc compressing the C5 root or a peripheral neuropathy affecting the musculocutaneous nerve.</li><li><b>Exaggerated Reflex (Hyperreflexia):</b> Suggests an upper motor neuron lesion, such as a stroke or spinal cord injury above the C5 level.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The biceps reflex, along with sensation over the lateral arm and deltoid/biceps strength, is a key part of the C5 neurological exam.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Biceps reflex</b> is a fundamental component of the neurological exam, providing a quick and reliable assessment of the C5 and C6 nerve roots and the integrity of the reflex arc through the cervical spinal cord.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Tap Biceps Tendon] --> B(Stretch Biceps Muscle); B --> C(Afferent Signal via Musculocutaneous N.); C --> D[C5/C6 Spinal Cord]; D --> E(Efferent Signal via Musculocutaneous N.); E --> F(Biceps Contraction/Elbow Flexion);"
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "tests_nerve_root",
