  "6c3a980e": {
    "title": "Bitemporal Hemianopia",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Endocrinology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Visual Field Defects"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Bitemporal hemianopia</b> is a specific type of partial blindness characterized by the loss of vision in the outer (temporal) halves of the visual fields of both eyes. It is classically caused by a lesion compressing the central part of the <mark>optic chiasm</mark>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Description:</b> Loss of the temporal (lateral) visual fields in both eyes, often described as \"tunnel vision.\"</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> The optic chiasm is where the nasal retinal fibers from each eye decussate (cross over). These nasal fibers are responsible for perceiving the temporal visual fields. A midline lesion at the chiasm selectively damages these crossing fibers.</li><li><b>Classic Cause:</b> The most common cause is a <mark>[[5f3188bd|pituitary adenoma]]</mark> growing upward from the sella turcica and compressing the chiasm from below.</li><li><b>Other Causes:</b> Other suprasellar masses like a [[7048db1e|craniopharyngioma]] or an aneurysm of the [[bd802d22|anterior communicating artery]] can also cause this defect.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient presenting with \"tunnel vision\" or complaining of bumping into things on either side, especially if accompanied by endocrine symptoms (e.g., galactorrhea, acromegaly), is a classic vignette for a [[5f3188bd|pituitary adenoma]] causing bitemporal hemianopia.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Bitemporal hemianopia</b> is the quintessential sign of optic chiasm compression, resulting from the selective damage to the crossing nasal retinal fibers and creating a characteristic 'tunnel vision' that points directly to a midline suprasellar pathology like a pituitary adenoma.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Lesion at Optic Chiasm] --Compresses--> B(Crossing Nasal Retinal Fibers); B --> C(Loss of Temporal Visual Fields); C --> D(Bitemporal Hemianopia);"
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_caused_by_lesion_at",
