  "dd47b9cc": {
    "title": "Blood-Brain Barrier (BBB)",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroanatomy",
      "Physiology",
      "Pharmacology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Blood-Brain Barrier"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Blood-Brain Barrier (BBB)</b> is a highly selective semipermeable border of endothelial cells that prevents solutes in the circulating blood from non-selectively crossing into the extracellular fluid of the central nervous system where neurons reside.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Key Components:</b><br>1. <b>[[5206aa83|Tight junctions]]</b> between non-fenestrated capillary endothelial cells.<br>2. A thick <b>[[c335e16d|Basement Membrane]]</b>.<br>3. <b>Astrocyte foot processes</b> that surround the capillary.</li><li><b>Function:</b> Protects the brain from circulating toxins, pathogens, and fluctuations in plasma composition. It maintains a stable CNS environment.</li><li><b>Transport Across BBB:</b><br> - <b>Lipid-soluble</b> substances (e.g., O<sub>2</sub>, CO<sub>2</sub>, anesthetics) can diffuse freely.<br> - <b>Water-soluble</b> substances (e.g., glucose, [[9115b704|amino acids]]) require specific <mark>carrier-mediated transport</mark>.</li><li><b>Circumventricular Organs:</b> Areas of the brain that lack a BBB, allowing them to monitor the chemical composition of the blood. These include the [[5dd343d3|area postrema]] (chemoreceptor trigger zone for vomiting) and parts of the [[89e86633|hypothalamus]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Breakdown of the BBB leads to vasogenic edema. Some antibiotics (e.g., penicillins) have poor CNS penetration but can cross an inflamed BBB during meningitis.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Blood-Brain Barrier</b> is a sophisticated neurovascular unit, not just a simple wall, that uses tight junctions, a robust basement membrane, and astrocyte support to create a highly regulated interface, ensuring the brain's chemical environment remains pristine and protected.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Capillary Lumen] --> B(Endothelial Cell); B --Tight Junctions--> B; B --> C(Basement Membrane); C --> D(Astrocyte Foot Processes); D --> E[Brain Parenchyma];"
    },
    "connections": [
