  "6ab4b0f2": {
    "title": "Blown Pupil",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Emergency Medicine",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Cranial Nerves"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>\"blown pupil\"</b> is a clinical term for a fixed, dilated pupil (mydriasis) that is nonreactive to light. It is a critical sign of compression of the [[68c66997|oculomotor nerve (CN III)]], often indicating a life-threatening increase in intracranial pressure.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism:</b> The parasympathetic fibers that control pupillary constriction run along the superficial, peripheral aspect of the [[68c66997|oculomotor nerve]]. These fibers are highly susceptible to external compression.</li><li><b>Classic Cause:</b> <mark>Uncal herniation</mark>, where the uncus of the temporal lobe herniates over the tentorium cerebelli and compresses the ipsilateral CN III.</li><li><b>Other Causes:</b> Aneurysm of the <mark>posterior communicating artery (PComA)</mark>, which is anatomically close to CN III, can also cause compression and a blown pupil.</li><li><b>Clinical Significance:</b> A unilateral blown pupil is an ominous sign of rapidly increasing intracranial pressure and impending brainstem compression. It is a neurosurgical emergency.</li><li><b>Associated Signs:</b> Often accompanied by other signs of a CN III palsy, such as ptosis and a \"down and out\" deviation of the eye.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> In a patient with head trauma and a deteriorating level of consciousness, the sudden appearance of a unilateral fixed and dilated pupil indicates uncal herniation and requires immediate intervention.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>A <b>blown pupil</b> is a neurological red flag, signaling compression of the parasympathetic fibers on the outside of the oculomotor nerve, most often by uncal herniation or a PComA aneurysm, and indicates a dire, time-sensitive emergency.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[‚Üë Intracranial Pressure] --> B(Uncal Herniation); B --Compresses--> C(CN III Parasympathetic Fibers); C --> D(Loss of Pupillary Constriction); D --> E(Fixed, Dilated Pupil);"
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_a_sign_of",
        "to": "oculomotor_nerve_compression"
      },
