  "aebb10eb": {
    "title": "Blowout Fracture",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Trauma",
      "Emergency Medicine",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Trauma"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>blowout fracture</b> is a traumatic fracture of the walls of the orbit, most commonly the orbital floor, caused by a sudden increase in intraorbital pressure from a direct blow to the globe (e.g., from a fist or a ball).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism:</b> A blunt, non-penetrating force strikes the globe, transmitting pressure throughout the orbit. The thin orbital floor (roof of the maxillary sinus) and/or medial wall (lamina papyracea of the ethmoid sinus) fracture, or 'blow out.'</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Patients present with periorbital pain, swelling, and ecchymosis. Key signs include <mark>diplopia on upward gaze</mark> and numbness of the cheek and upper teeth.</li><li><b>Muscle Entrapment:</b> The fracture can entrap the <mark>inferior rectus muscle</mark> and/or orbital fat. This entrapment restricts upward movement of the eye, causing vertical diplopia, especially on upgaze.</li><li><b>Nerve Injury:</b> The fracture of the orbital floor can damage the <mark>infraorbital nerve</mark> (a branch of CN V<sub>2</sub>), leading to paresthesia or numbness of the ipsilateral cheek, upper lip, and upper gingiva.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The combination of a history of blunt eye trauma, diplopia on upward gaze, and numbness of the cheek is classic for an orbital blowout fracture with inferior rectus entrapment and infraorbital nerve injury.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>A <b>blowout fracture</b> is a hydraulic fracture of the thin orbital floor, where the force of a blow to the eye is transmitted to the surrounding bone, leading to entrapment of the inferior rectus muscle and injury to the infraorbital nerve, manifesting as an inability to look up and a numb cheek.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "can_cause_entrapment_of",
        "to": "inferior_rectus_muscle"
      },
