  "84b10400": {
    "title": "Botulinum Toxin",
    "primaryType": "drug",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Neurology",
      "Microbiology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Skeletal Muscle Relaxants"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Botulinum toxin</b> is a potent neurotoxin produced by the bacterium <i>Clostridium botulinum</i>. It causes flaccid paralysis by inhibiting the presynaptic release of [[6a005559|acetylcholine]] at the neuromuscular junction. In small, purified doses, it is used therapeutically for a variety of medical and cosmetic purposes.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> The toxin is a protease that cleaves <mark>SNARE proteins</mark> (e.g., SNAP-25, synaptobrevin), which are essential for the fusion of acetylcholine-containing vesicles with the presynaptic membrane. This prevents ACh release.</li><li><b>Medical Uses:</b><br> - <b>Spasticity/Dystonia:</b> Treats focal dystonias (e.g., torticollis, blepharospasm), spasticity in [[171ca00b|cerebral palsy]] and [[45dd6d19|multiple sclerosis]].<br> - <b>Pain:</b> Prophylaxis for chronic [[c8833bae|migraine headaches]].<br> - <b>Other:</b> Hyperhidrosis (excessive sweating), strabismus.</li><li><b>Cosmetic Use:</b> Injected to reduce facial wrinkles by temporarily paralyzing underlying muscles (Botox).</li><li><b>Toxicity (Botulism):</b> Ingestion of the toxin (e.g., from improperly canned foods) causes botulism, a life-threatening illness characterized by descending flaccid paralysis, diplopia, dysphagia, and respiratory failure.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember that botulinum toxin causes a <u>presynaptic</u> blockade of ACh release, which contrasts with myasthenia gravis (postsynaptic receptor blockade) and Lambert-Eaton syndrome (presynaptic Ca<sup>2+</sup> channel blockade).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Botulinum toxin</b> induces paralysis by enzymatically snipping the SNARE proteins required for acetylcholine release at the neuromuscular junction; this potent biological mechanism is harnessed in medicine to selectively weaken overactive muscles in conditions from dystonia to cosmetic wrinkles.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Botulinum Toxin] --> B(Cleaves SNARE Proteins); B --x C(Vesicle Fusion); C --x D(ACh Release); D --x E(Muscle Contraction); E --> F(Flaccid Paralysis);"
    },
    "connections": [
