  "ac55d026": {
    "title": "Brachioradialis Reflex",
    "primaryType": "physiology",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Physical Exam",
      "Physiology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Spinal Cord"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Brachioradialis reflex</b> is a deep tendon reflex that causes flexion of the elbow and supination of the forearm when the brachioradialis tendon is tapped at the styloid process of the radius. It is used to test the integrity of the <mark>C5 and C6</mark> spinal nerve roots and the radial nerve.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Nerve Roots:</b> Primarily tests the <b>C6</b> nerve root, with a contribution from C5. Mnemonic: C5, <b>6</b>, pick up sticks.</li><li><b>Pathway:</b> Tapping the tendon stretches the brachioradialis muscle. The afferent signal travels via the radial nerve to the C5/C6 spinal cord segments, synapses with a motor neuron, and the efferent signal returns via the radial nerve to cause muscle contraction.</li><li><b>Diminished/Absent Reflex:</b> Suggests a lower motor neuron lesion, such as a herniated disc compressing the C6 root or a peripheral neuropathy affecting the radial nerve.</li><li><b>Exaggerated Reflex (Hyperreflexia):</b> Suggests an upper motor neuron lesion, such as a stroke or spinal cord injury above the C5/C6 level.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The brachioradialis reflex, along with the biceps reflex, is a key part of assessing the C5 and C6 nerve roots.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Brachioradialis reflex</b> is a specific test for the C5-C6 nerve roots, elicited by tapping the distal radius, which provides valuable information for localizing lesions within the cervical spine and brachial plexus.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Tap Brachioradialis Tendon] --> B(Stretch Muscle); B --> C(Afferent Signal via Radial N.); C --> D[C5/C6 Spinal Cord]; D --> E(Efferent Signal via Radial N.); E --> F(Elbow Flexion/Forearm Supination);"
    },
