  "a584135d": {
    "title": "Brain",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroanatomy",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Central Nervous System"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Brain</b> is the central organ of the human nervous system, responsible for thought, memory, emotion, touch, motor skills, vision, breathing, temperature, hunger, and every process that regulates our body. It is composed of the cerebrum, cerebellum, and brainstem.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Embryology:</b> Develops from the rostral part of the neural tube, which differentiates into the forebrain (prosencephalon), midbrain (mesencephalon), and hindbrain (rhombencephalon).</li><li><b>Major Parts:</b><br> - <b>Cerebrum:</b> The largest part, divided into two hemispheres, responsible for higher cognitive functions.<br> - <b>Cerebellum:</b> Located under the cerebrum, coordinates muscle movements and balance.<br> - <b>Brainstem:</b> Connects the cerebrum and cerebellum to the spinal cord, controlling many automatic functions like breathing and heart rate.</li><li><b>Vascular Supply:</b> Supplied by the anterior circulation (from internal carotid arteries) and posterior circulation (from vertebral arteries), which connect via the [[e22300e8|Circle of Willis]].</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> Can be affected by a wide range of pathologies including [[c5da3c57|ischemic]] and [[hemorrhagic_stroke|hemorrhagic strokes]], [[be057cfc|tumors]], trauma, infection, and neurodegenerative diseases.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Understanding the functional localization within the brain (e.g., motor/sensory homunculus, language areas) and the vascular territories is crucial for solving clinical neurology questions.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Brain</b> is the command center of the body, where intricate networks of neurons process information and control function, with specific regions highly specialized for distinct tasks, making the clinical presentation of brain lesions highly predictable based on their location.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_part_of",
        "to": "central_nervous_system"
      },
      {
        "type": "develops_from",
        "to": "neural_tube"
      },
      {
        "type": "can_be_affected_by",
        "to": "c5da3c57"
      },
      {
