  "1777e176": {
    "title": "Brain Death",
    "primaryType": "concept",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Critical Care",
      "Medical Ethics",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Coma"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Brain death</b> is the irreversible cessation of all functions of the entire brain, including the brainstem. It is a legal and clinical definition of death, distinct from a persistent vegetative state where brainstem functions may be intact.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Criteria:</b> Diagnosis requires evidence of an irreversible cause of coma, absence of confounding factors (e.g., hypothermia, drug intoxication), and the absence of all brainstem reflexes.</li><li><b>Brainstem Reflexes Tested:</b> Pupillary light reflex, corneal reflex, oculocephalic reflex (doll's eyes), oculovestibular reflex (cold caloric), gag reflex, and cough reflex must all be absent.</li><li><b>Apnea Test:</b> A definitive test where the patient is disconnected from the ventilator to see if a rise in PaCO<sub>2</sub> stimulates a spontaneous respiratory effort. Absence of breathing despite a high PaCO<sub>2</sub> confirms apnea.</li><li><b>Cerebral Perfusion:</b> In brain death, [[3eca3f19|cerebral perfusion pressure (CPP)]] is zero, meaning there is no cerebral blood flow.</li><li><b>Ethical/Legal Status:</b> A patient who meets the criteria for brain death is legally and medically deceased, even if their heart continues to beat with mechanical ventilation. This allows for the cessation of life support and consideration of organ donation.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Brain death</b> signifies the irreversible loss of function of the entire brain, including the brainstem, which is confirmed by the absence of all brainstem reflexes and a positive apnea test, establishing legal death despite ongoing cardiac activity on life support.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
