  "e9a47751": {
    "title": "Brain Injury",
    "primaryType": "pathology",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Trauma",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Trauma"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Brain injury</b> is damage to the brain that can result from a traumatic force (Traumatic Brain Injury, TBI) or a non-traumatic event (e.g., stroke, anoxia). The clinical effects depend on the mechanism, location, and severity of the injury.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Traumatic Brain Injury (TBI):</b> Includes concussions, contusions, [[22b22e08|diffuse axonal injury]], and intracranial hemorrhages (epidural, subdural). Caused by external forces.</li><li><b>Non-Traumatic Brain Injury:</b> Includes [[c5da3c57|ischemic]] and [[hemorrhagic_stroke|hemorrhagic strokes]], anoxic brain injury (e.g., from cardiac arrest), infections, and tumors.</li><li><b>Primary vs. Secondary Injury:</b><br> - <b>Primary Injury:</b> The initial damage that occurs at the moment of impact or insult (e.g., shearing of axons, laceration of vessels).<br> - <b>Secondary Injury:</b> A cascade of molecular and inflammatory events that occur in the hours and days following the primary injury (e.g., cerebral edema, excitotoxicity, inflammation), which often worsens the overall outcome.</li><li><b>Stroke Effects:</b> The neurological deficits from a stroke are highly predictable based on the affected [[105efab1|arterial supply]] and the function of the brain region it perfuses (e.g., [[143bb23d|MCA stroke]] causing contralateral face/arm weakness).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Understanding the vascular territories of the major cerebral arteries ([[830c856c|ACA]], [[143bb23d|MCA]], [[b6a2cc31|PCA]]) is essential for localizing stroke lesions based on clinical symptoms.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Brain injury</b> encompasses a spectrum of damage from various causes, with the final clinical outcome determined not only by the initial insult but also by the subsequent cascade of secondary injury processes like edema and inflammation, which are major targets for neuroprotective therapies.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
