  "be057cfc": {
    "title": "Brain Tumors",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Oncology",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Brain Tumors"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Brain tumors</b> are neoplasms originating in the intracranial tissues. They can be primary (arising from brain cells) or metastatic (spreading from cancers elsewhere in the body). Their clinical presentation depends on their location, size, and growth rate.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Adult Primary Tumors:</b> Most are supratentorial. In order of frequency: [[b6bbd0bc|Glioblastoma]], [[e98ea0ba|Meningioma]], [[03ecb69e|Schwannoma]], Oligodendroglioma.</li><li><b>Childhood Primary Tumors:</b> Most are infratentorial. In order of frequency: Pilocytic astrocytoma, [[16d613bb|Medulloblastoma]], [[14365ef4|Ependymoma]].</li><li><b>Metastatic Tumors:</b> More common than primary tumors. Often present as multiple, well-circumscribed lesions at the gray-white junction. Common primary sources are <mark>Lung, Breast, Kidney, Melanoma, and Colon</mark>.</li><li><b>General Symptoms:</b> Headaches (often worse in the morning), seizures, and focal neurological deficits corresponding to the tumor's location.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A ring-enhancing lesion on MRI with contrast is a key finding. The differential includes [[b6bbd0bc|glioblastoma]], metastasis, and abscess. A 'butterfly' appearance crossing the corpus callosum is classic for glioblastoma.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The classification and prognosis of <b>brain tumors</b> differ significantly between adults and children, with adults more commonly developing aggressive supratentorial gliomas and children typically having more benign infratentorial tumors.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
