  "0f0fbfa0": {
    "title": "Branch Retinal Vein Occlusion (BRVO)",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Retinal Disorders"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>Branch Retinal Vein Occlusion (BRVO)</b> is the blockage of a small vein in the retina, leading to hemorrhage, edema, and potential vision loss in the quadrant of the retina drained by that vein.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Most commonly occurs at an <mark>arteriovenous (AV) crossing</mark>, where a hardened, atherosclerotic retinal arteriole compresses the adjacent, thinner-walled venule, leading to turbulent flow and thrombus formation.</li><li><b>Risk Factors:</b> Strongly associated with systemic vascular diseases like <mark>hypertension</mark>, diabetes mellitus, and hyperlipidemia.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Sudden, painless, unilateral vision loss, which may be described as a scotoma (blind spot) or blurry vision in a specific part of the visual field.</li><li><b>Fundoscopy:</b> Fundoscopic exam reveals <mark>sectoral (quadrantic) retinal hemorrhages</mark>, venous engorgement, and cotton-wool spots confined to the area drained by the occluded vein.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Differentiate from Central Retinal Vein Occlusion (CRVO), which involves the entire retina and has a more dramatic \"blood and thunder\" appearance. BRVO is localized to a quadrant. The key association is hypertension causing AV nicking.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>A <b>Branch Retinal Vein Occlusion</b> is a consequence of systemic vascular disease playing out in the eye, where a stiff arteriole compresses a venule at a crossing point, causing a localized 'traffic jam' of blood that results in a sectoral retinal hemorrhage.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Hypertension/Atherosclerosis] --> B(Arteriolar Sclerosis); B --> C(Compression of Vein at AV Crossing); C --> D(Thrombus Formation); D --> E(Branch Retinal Vein Occlusion); E --> F(Sectoral Hemorrhage & Edema);"
    },
