  "2fcee185": {
    "title": "Brimonidine",
    "primaryType": "drug",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Autonomic",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Glaucoma Therapy"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Brimonidine</b> is a highly selective <i>Œ±<sub>2</sub>-adrenergic agonist</i> used as a topical eye drop to lower intraocular pressure (IOP) in the treatment of [[5ea7b741|open-angle glaucoma]] and ocular hypertension.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Has a dual mechanism. It primarily <mark>decreases aqueous humor synthesis</mark> by stimulating Œ±<sub>2</sub> receptors on the ciliary body. It also <mark>increases uveoscleral outflow</mark>.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> A common agent for the long-term management of [[5ea7b741|open-angle glaucoma]].</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Ocular side effects include allergic conjunctivitis, hyperemia (redness), and pruritus (itching). Systemic side effects are possible due to absorption and include dry mouth, sedation, and fatigue. Unlike apraclonidine, it does not cause mydriasis and can be used in angle-closure glaucoma.</li><li><b>Comparison:</b> Similar to [[c1f67280|apraclonidine]] but is more selective for the Œ±<sub>2</sub> receptor and has a lower incidence of allergic reactions and tachyphylaxis, making it more suitable for long-term use.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember that Œ±<sub>2</sub> agonists like brimonidine and clonidine act as sympatholytics, reducing sympathetic outflow. In the eye, this leads to decreased aqueous humor production.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Brimonidine</b> is an effective glaucoma medication that lowers intraocular pressure through a dual mechanism of decreasing aqueous humor production and increasing its outflow, all mediated by its selective Œ±<sub>2</sub>-adrenergic agonism.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Brimonidine] --> B(Stimulates Œ±2 Receptors); B --> C(‚Üì Aqueous Humor Synthesis); B --> D(‚Üë Uveoscleral Outflow); C & D --> E(‚Üì Intraocular Pressure);"
    },
