    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Bromocriptine</b> is an ergot derivative that acts as a <i>dopamine D<sub>2</sub> receptor agonist</i>. It is used to treat conditions associated with hyperprolactinemia and [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Stimulates dopamine D<sub>2</sub> receptors in the CNS and periphery.</li><li><b>Clinical Use (Endocrinology):</b> Treats hyperprolactinemia and prolactinomas by stimulating D<sub>2</sub> receptors on lactotrophs in the anterior pituitary, which inhibits prolactin secretion. Also used for acromegaly as it can suppress GH secretion.</li><li><b>Clinical Use (Neurology):</b> Used as an adjunctive therapy in [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]] to stimulate dopamine receptors in the striatum. It is an ergot derivative and is less commonly used now than non-ergot agonists (e.g., pramipexole, ropinirole) due to its side effect profile.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Nausea, vomiting, postural hypotension, and headache. As an ergot derivative, it can cause pulmonary fibrosis and vasospasm.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Bromocriptine is a classic treatment for prolactinomas. Remember that dopamine tonically inhibits prolactin release, so a dopamine agonist will lower prolactin levels.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Bromocriptine</b> is a dopamine D<sub>2</sub> agonist that leverages dopamine's inhibitory control over prolactin to treat hyperprolactinemia and supplements dopamine signaling in the basal ganglia to treat Parkinson disease, though its use is limited by its ergot-related side effects.</p>",
