      "definition": "<p><b>Brown-S√©quard syndrome</b> is a rare neurological condition caused by <i>hemisection of the spinal cord</i>, resulting in a characteristic pattern of ipsilateral motor and proprioceptive loss, and contralateral pain and temperature sensory loss below the level of the lesion.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Typically caused by trauma, such as a penetrating injury (e.g., stab wound) or a tumor compressing one half of the spinal cord.</li><li><b>Ipsilateral Deficits (at and below lesion):</b><br> - <b>Motor:</b> Ipsilateral spastic paralysis below the lesion (corticospinal tract damage).<br> - <b>Sensation:</b> Ipsilateral loss of proprioception, vibration, and fine touch below the lesion ([[e7f5cbbe|dorsal column]] damage).</li><li><b>Contralateral Deficits (below lesion):</b><br> - <b>Sensation:</b> Contralateral loss of pain and temperature sensation, typically beginning 1-2 segments below the lesion (spinothalamic tract damage, as fibers decussate in the spinal cord).</li><li><b>Deficits at the Level of the Lesion:</b><br> - Ipsilateral flaccid paralysis (LMN damage at that level).<br> - Ipsilateral complete loss of all sensation.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> This syndrome is a classic test of spinal cord tract anatomy. The key is remembering which tracts cross in the medulla (dorsal columns, corticospinal) versus the spinal cord (spinothalamic). If the lesion is above T1, an ipsilateral [[c19010a3|Horner syndrome]] may also be present.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Brown-S√©quard syndrome</b> is the ultimate clinical demonstration of spinal cord neuroanatomy, creating a striking dissociation of deficits where one side of the body loses motor function and proprioception, while the other side loses the ability to feel pain and temperature, all due to a unilateral cord lesion.</p>",
