    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Bulbar palsy</b> refers to a set of clinical signs resulting from damage to the <u>lower motor neurons (LMNs)</u> of the cranial nerves originating in the brainstem (medulla oblongata, or 'bulb'). Specifically, it involves cranial nerves IX (glossopharyngeal), X (vagus), XI (accessory), and XII (hypoglossal).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Caused by LMN lesions of cranial nerves IX, X, XI, and XII.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Characterized by <mark>flaccid weakness</mark> of the muscles of the mouth, pharynx, and larynx. This leads to dysarthria (slurred speech), dysphagia (difficulty swallowing), drooling, and a hoarse or nasal voice.</li><li><b>Physical Exam Findings:</b> On examination, there is tongue wasting and <mark>fasciculations</'mark> (LMN signs), a diminished or absent gag reflex, and the palate may not elevate symmetrically.</li><li><b>Causes:</b> Can be seen in [[4ed629f9|Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS)]], Guillain-Barr√© syndrome, myasthenia gravis, and brainstem strokes or tumors.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Differentiate from <b>pseudobulbar palsy</b>, which is caused by <u>upper motor neuron (UMN)</u> lesions. Pseudobulbar palsy presents with a spastic dysarthria, an exaggerated gag reflex, and emotional lability (pseudobulbar affect), without tongue atrophy or fasciculations.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Bulbar palsy</b> is a manifestation of lower motor neuron damage to the lower cranial nerves, resulting in a flaccid paralysis of the oral, pharyngeal, and laryngeal muscles, which must be distinguished from the spastic paralysis of the same muscles seen in the upper motor neuron condition, pseudobulbar palsy.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
