    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Bupivacaine</b> is a long-acting, amide-type <i>local anesthetic</i> commonly used for regional anesthesia, such as epidurals for labor and spinal anesthesia for surgical procedures.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Blocks voltage-gated Na<sup>+</sup> channels in nerve membranes, preventing the generation and conduction of nerve impulses.</li><li><b>Class:</b> Amide local anesthetic (has two 'i's in its name).</li><li><b>Pharmacokinetics:</b> Has a long duration of action, making it suitable for prolonged procedures and postoperative pain control.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Widely used for epidural analgesia, spinal anesthesia, and peripheral nerve blocks.</li><li><b>Adverse Effect:</b> The most notable adverse effect is <mark>severe cardiotoxicity</mark>. It is more cardiotoxic than other local anesthetics. Accidental intravascular injection can lead to severe ventricular arrhythmias and cardiovascular collapse that is difficult to resuscitate.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember bupivacaine for its long duration of action and its significant risk of cardiotoxicity. This risk is a major consideration in its clinical use and dosing.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Bupivacaine</b> is a potent, long-acting amide anesthetic favored for epidurals and nerve blocks, but its use is shadowed by a significant risk of severe cardiotoxicity if accidentally injected systemically.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
