    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Butorphanol</b> is a synthetic opioid analgesic that functions as a <i>mixed agonist-antagonist</i>. It is primarily used for the management of moderate to severe pain.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Acts as a <mark>Œ∫-opioid receptor agonist</mark> and a <mark>Œº-opioid receptor partial agonist or weak antagonist</mark>.</li><li><b>Analgesic Effect:</b> The Œ∫-agonist activity provides strong analgesia.</li><li><b>Ceiling Effect:</b> Like other mixed agonist-antagonists, it exhibits a ceiling effect for respiratory depression, making it potentially safer in overdose compared to full Œº-agonists.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Used for moderate to severe pain, particularly in labor (less neonatal respiratory depression) and for postoperative pain. Also available as a nasal spray for [[c8833bae|migraines]].</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Can cause sedation, nausea, and psychotomimetic effects (e.g., hallucinations, dysphoria) due to Œ∫-receptor agonism. It can precipitate withdrawal symptoms in patients physically dependent on full Œº-opioid agonists.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember that mixed agonist-antagonists like butorphanol and nalbuphine can precipitate withdrawal in opioid-dependent patients. Their primary analgesic effect comes from Œ∫-agonism.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Butorphanol</b> is a mixed-action opioid that provides potent analgesia through Œ∫-receptor agonism while having a limited effect on Œº-receptors, which gives it a better safety profile regarding respiratory depression but also the potential to induce withdrawal in opioid-dependent individuals.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
