    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Cabergoline</b> is a long-acting ergot derivative that is a potent <i>dopamine D<sub>2</sub> receptor agonist</i>. It is the first-line treatment for hyperprolactinemia and prolactin-secreting [[5f3188bd|pituitary adenomas]] (prolactinomas).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Stimulates D<sub>2</sub> receptors on lactotrophs in the [[76ba7f2e|anterior pituitary]], mimicking the natural inhibitory effect of dopamine on prolactin secretion. This leads to a decrease in serum prolactin levels and can cause shrinkage of prolactinomas.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> <u>First-line treatment</u> for prolactinomas and hyperprolactinemia. Also used in [[acromegaly]] (can suppress GH secretion) and [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]].</li><li><b>Pharmacokinetics:</b> Has a long half-life, allowing for once or twice weekly dosing, which improves patient compliance compared to [[d24a5ff0|bromocriptine]].</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Nausea, headache, postural hypotension. Less nausea than bromocriptine. High doses have been associated with valvular heart disease, but this is rare at the doses used for hyperprolactinemia.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Cabergoline is preferred over [[d24a5ff0|bromocriptine]] for treating prolactinomas due to its higher efficacy, better side-effect profile, and more convenient dosing schedule.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Cabergoline</b> is the superior dopamine agonist for treating hyperprolactinemia, effectively suppressing prolactin secretion and shrinking pituitary tumors by powerfully stimulating D<sub>2</sub> receptors, with the clinical advantage of a long half-life and better tolerability.</p>",
