    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Caf√©-au-lait spots</b> are well-demarcated, hyperpigmented macules or patches on the skin, with a color resembling 'coffee with milk.' While a few small spots can be normal, the presence of multiple, large spots is a hallmark of several genetic syndromes, most notably Neurofibromatosis Type 1.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Description:</b> Flat, pigmented birthmarks with a light brown color and distinct borders.</li><li><b>Neurofibromatosis Type 1 (NF-1):</b> The presence of <mark>six or more</mark> caf√©-au-lait spots greater than 5 mm in diameter in prepubertal individuals (or >15 mm in postpubertal individuals) is a key diagnostic criterion for NF-1. The spots in NF-1 typically have smooth borders ('coast of California').</li><li><b>McCune-Albright Syndrome:</b> Characterized by a triad of fibrous dysplasia of bone, endocrine abnormalities (like precocious puberty), and large, unilateral caf√©-au-lait spots with irregular, jagged borders ('coast of Maine').</li><li><b>Other Associations:</b> Can also be seen in tuberous sclerosis, Fanconi anemia, and other syndromes, but are most strongly associated with NF-1.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Multiple caf√©-au-lait spots in a child should prompt a thorough evaluation for other signs of Neurofibromatosis Type 1, such as axillary freckling, Lisch nodules, and neurofibromas.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>While often benign, multiple <b>caf√©-au-lait spots</b> are a crucial dermatological clue to underlying systemic genetic disorders, with the number and border characteristics (smooth in NF-1, irregular in McCune-Albright) helping to narrow the differential diagnosis.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "is_a_sign_of",
        "to": "neurofibromatosis_type_1"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_a_sign_of",
        "to": "mccune_albright_syndrome"
      }
    ]
