  "24d36d58": {
    "title": "Calcitonin Gene-Related Peptide (CGRP)",
    "primaryType": "molecule",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Physiology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Neurotransmitters"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Calcitonin Gene-Related Peptide (CGRP)</b> is a 37-amino acid neuropeptide that is widely distributed in the central and peripheral nervous systems. It is a potent vasodilator and is critically involved in pain transmission, particularly in the pathophysiology of [[c8833bae|migraine headaches]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Function:</b> Acts as a potent arterial vasodilator and a neurotransmitter/neuromodulator in pain pathways.</li><li><b>Role in Migraine:</b> During a migraine attack, CGRP is released from trigeminal nerve endings. This release causes vasodilation of cranial blood vessels and promotes neurogenic inflammation, contributing to the pain of a migraine.</li><li><b>Therapeutic Target:</b> CGRP and its receptor have become major targets for migraine therapy.</li><li><b>Drug Classes Targeting CGRP:</b><br>1. <b>[[4770b8a2|Anti-CGRP Monoclonal Antibodies]]</b> (e.g., erenumab, galcanezumab): Used for migraine <u>prophylaxis</u>.<br>2. <b>Gepants</b> (e.g., ubrogepant, rimegepant): Small molecule CGRP receptor antagonists used for <u>acute</u> treatment of migraines.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The central role of CGRP in migraine pathophysiology is a high-yield concept. Understand that blocking the CGRP pathway, either with monoclonal antibodies for prevention or gepants for acute attacks, is a modern, targeted approach to migraine treatment.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Calcitonin Gene-Related Peptide (CGRP)</b> is a key player in the generation of migraine pain, acting as both a powerful vasodilator and a pain-signaling molecule in the trigeminal system, making its blockade a highly effective strategy for migraine therapy.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Trigeminal Nerve Activation] --> B(Release of CGRP); B --> C(Vasodilation & Neurogenic Inflammation); C --> D(Migraine Pain);"
    },
    "connections": [
