  "c1ad76f4": {
    "title": "Carbachol",
    "primaryType": "drug",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Autonomic",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Glaucoma Therapy"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Carbachol</b> is a <i>cholinomimetic agent</i> that acts as a non-selective agonist at both muscarinic and nicotinic acetylcholine receptors. It is primarily used in ophthalmology to treat glaucoma.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> As a direct cholinergic agonist, it mimics the effects of [[6a005559|acetylcholine]]. In the eye, it stimulates muscarinic (M<sub>3</sub>) receptors on the ciliary muscle and the sphincter pupillae muscle.</li><li><b>Ocular Effects:</b><br> 1. <b>Miosis:</b> Contraction of the sphincter pupillae muscle causes pupillary constriction.<br> 2. <b>‚Üì IOP:</b> Contraction of the ciliary muscle increases the outflow of aqueous humor through the trabecular meshwork, lowering intraocular pressure.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Used topically to treat [[5ea7b741|open-angle glaucoma]] and to produce miosis during ophthalmic surgery. It is less commonly used than pilocarpine.</li><li><b>Resistance to AChE:</b> Carbachol is resistant to hydrolysis by acetylcholinesterase, giving it a longer duration of action than acetylcholine.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember carbachol as a direct-acting cholinomimetic that lowers IOP by increasing trabecular outflow, a mechanism shared with pilocarpine.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Carbachol</b> is a potent, long-acting acetylcholine mimic that effectively lowers intraocular pressure in glaucoma by contracting the ciliary muscle to open up the trabecular meshwork drainage channels.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
