  "541cd176": {
    "title": "Carbidopa/Levodopa",
    "primaryType": "drug",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Neurology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Parkinson Disease Therapy"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Carbidopa/Levodopa</b> (trade name Sinemet) is the most effective and widely used combination drug for the symptomatic treatment of [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]]. Levodopa is a metabolic precursor to dopamine, while carbidopa is a peripheral DOPA decarboxylase inhibitor.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b><br> - <b>Levodopa (L-DOPA):</b> Can cross the [[dd47b9cc|blood-brain barrier]] (unlike dopamine) and is converted to [[90adc821|dopamine]] in the CNS by DOPA decarboxylase, replenishing the depleted dopamine stores in the striatum.<br> - <b>Carbidopa:</b> Inhibits peripheral DOPA decarboxylase. This prevents the conversion of L-DOPA to dopamine in the periphery, which <mark>increases the bioavailability of L-DOPA in the brain</mark> and <mark>reduces peripheral side effects</mark> (like nausea and arrhythmias).</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> The cornerstone of treatment for [[58c8ea03|Parkinson disease]], particularly effective for bradykinesia and rigidity.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Nausea, hallucinations, postural hypotension. Long-term use is associated with motor fluctuations ('on-off' phenomenon) and dyskinesias (involuntary movements).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The rationale for the combination is key: Carbidopa acts as a 'bodyguard' for Levodopa, ensuring more of it reaches the brain where it's needed, while minimizing side effects elsewhere in the body.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Carbidopa/Levodopa</b> combination is a brilliant pharmacological strategy that overcomes the blood-brain barrier by using a precursor (Levodopa) and then protecting that precursor from peripheral breakdown (with Carbidopa) to effectively deliver dopamine to the deficient basal ganglia in Parkinson's disease.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Levodopa] --Peripheral DOPA Decarboxylase--> B(Dopamine - Periphery); C[Carbidopa] --x B; A --> D(Crosses BBB); D --> E[L-DOPA in CNS]; E --Central DOPA Decarboxylase--> F(Dopamine - CNS); F --> G(Treats Parkinson's Symptoms);"
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "treats",
        "to": "58c8ea03"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_a_precursor_to",
        "to": "90adc821"
      },
