  "e1e7ac22": {
    "title": "Carotid-Cavernous Fistula",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Vascular",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Cerebrovascular Disease"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>Carotid-Cavernous Fistula (CCF)</b> is an abnormal communication between the internal carotid artery and the [[c260efc8|cavernous sinus]]. This creates a high-flow, high-pressure arteriovenous shunt within the sinus, leading to a characteristic set of signs and symptoms.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Can be traumatic (e.g., from a basal skull fracture) or spontaneous (e.g., from a ruptured intracavernous carotid aneurysm).</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Arterial blood from the internal carotid artery flows directly into the low-pressure [[c260efc8|cavernous sinus]]. This increases pressure in the sinus and reverses blood flow in the veins that drain into it, particularly the superior ophthalmic vein.</li><li><b>Clinical Triad:</b> The classic triad is <mark>pulsatile exophthalmos</mark> (protruding, pulsating eye), <mark>ocular bruit</mark> (a whooshing sound heard over the eye), and <mark>chemosis</mark> (conjunctival edema and redness).</li><li><b>Other Symptoms:</b> Patients also develop ophthalmoplegia (paralysis of eye muscles) due to dysfunction of cranial nerves III, IV, and VI, which all traverse the cavernous sinus. There may also be sensory loss in the V<sub>1</sub> and V<sub>2</sub> distribution.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The combination of a pulsating eye and an audible bruit over the eye after head trauma is pathognomonic for a carotid-cavernous fistula.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>A <b>Carotid-Cavernous Fistula</b> creates a high-pressure vascular storm within the cavernous sinus, engorging the orbital veins and compressing the cranial nerves that pass through it, resulting in the dramatic clinical picture of a pulsating, red, and paralyzed eye.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Internal Carotid Artery] --Fistula--> B(Cavernous Sinus); B --> C(‚Üë Pressure in Sinus); C --> D(Reversal of flow in Superior Ophthalmic Vein); D --> E(Pulsatile Exophthalmos, Chemosis, Bruit); C --> F(Compression of CN III, IV, V1, V2, VI); F --> G(Ophthalmoplegia, Sensory Loss);"
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "affects",
        "to": "c260efc8"
      },
      {
        "type": "causes",
        "to": "ophthalmoplegia"
      },
      {
        "type": "presents_with",
        "to": "pulsatile_exophthalmos"
      }
    ]
  },
  "6696dd3a": {
    "title": "Carteolol",
    "primaryType": "drug",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pharmacology",
      "Glaucoma Therapy"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Carteolol</b> is a non-selective <i>Œ≤-adrenergic antagonist</i> (beta-blocker) used as a topical eye drop to reduce intraocular pressure (IOP) in the treatment of [[5ea7b741|open-angle glaucoma]] and ocular hypertension.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism of Action:</b> Blocks both Œ≤<sub>1</sub> and Œ≤<sub>2</sub> adrenergic receptors on the ciliary epithelium. This leads to a <mark>decrease in aqueous humor production</mark>, thereby lowering IOP.</li><li><b>Class:</b> Non-selective beta-blocker, similar to [[ae28be6c|timolol]].</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> A first-line agent for [[5ea7b741|open-angle glaucoma]].</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Ocular side effects include stinging and burning. Systemic absorption can occur, potentially causing bradycardia, hypotension, fatigue, and bronchoconstriction.</li><li><b>Contraindications:</b> Should be used with caution in patients with asthma, COPD, bradycardia, or heart block due to its non-selective Œ≤-blockade.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Like all non-selective beta-blockers used for glaucoma, carteolol's main mechanism is decreasing aqueous humor production. Be aware of the potential for systemic side effects, especially bronchospasm in patients with reactive airway disease.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Carteolol</b> is a non-selective beta-blocker that effectively treats glaucoma by turning down the 'faucet' of aqueous humor production in the ciliary body, but its systemic absorption carries the risk of Œ≤-blockade side effects throughout the body.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
