  "85f03b02": {
    "title": "Cataracts",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Geriatrics",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Ophthalmology",
      "Lens Disorders"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>cataract</b> is a painless, progressive opacification or clouding of the normally clear lens of the eye, which leads to a decrease in vision. It is the leading cause of blindness worldwide.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Involves the denaturation and aggregation of lens proteins (crystallins), leading to loss of transparency and light scattering.</li><li><b>Risk Factors:</b> <mark>Increased age</mark> is the most common risk factor. Others include smoking, excessive alcohol use, excessive sunlight (UV) exposure, prolonged glucocorticoid use, trauma, and infection.</li><li><b>Systemic Disease Associations:</b> <mark>Diabetes mellitus</mark> (due to sorbitol accumulation via aldose reductase), classic galactosemia, galactokinase deficiency, and myotonic dystrophy.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Patients report painless, progressive blurring of vision, glare (especially at night with oncoming headlights), and often a myopic shift (nearsightedness). On exam, there is loss of the red reflex and the lens appears opaque.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> The definitive treatment is surgical removal of the opacified lens and replacement with an artificial intraocular lens.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember the association with diabetes and galactosemia, where excess sugars are converted to osmotically active polyols (sorbitol, galactitol) in the lens, causing hydropic swelling and opacification.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Cataracts</b> represent a clouding of the eye's lens due to protein aggregation, most commonly as a part of aging, which scatters light and causes progressive, painless vision loss that can only be definitively treated by surgical lens replacement.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
