    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Cauda Equina</b> (Latin for \"horse's tail\") is the bundle of spinal nerves and spinal nerve rootlets, consisting of the second through fifth lumbar nerve pairs, the first through fifth sacral nerve pairs, and the coccygeal nerve, all of which arise from the lumbar enlargement and the conus medullaris of the spinal cord.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Anatomy:</b> Comprises the nerve roots from L2 to Co1 that descend through the lumbar cistern (subarachnoid space) below the termination of the spinal cord proper (conus medullaris, typically at L1-L2).</li><li><b>Function:</b> These nerve roots provide motor and sensory innervation to the lower extremities, perineum, and pelvic organs (including the bladder and anal sphincters).</li><li><b>Clinical Significance:</b> Compression of these nerve roots leads to <mark>[[2904b5c8|Cauda Equina Syndrome]]</mark>, a neurosurgical emergency.</li><li><b>Lumbar Puncture:</b> The cauda equina floats in the cerebrospinal fluid of the lumbar cistern, which is the target for a lumbar puncture. The needle is typically inserted at the L3-L4 or L4-L5 interspace to avoid injuring the spinal cord.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember that the spinal cord ends at L1-L2 in adults. The collection of nerve roots continuing down the vertebral canal below this level is the cauda equina.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Cauda Equina</b> is the collection of descending lumbar and sacral nerve roots that resemble a horse's tail, filling the subarachnoid space below the end of the spinal cord; its compression results in the surgical emergency known as cauda equina syndrome.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
