    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Cauda Equina Syndrome</b> is a neurosurgical emergency caused by severe compression of the [[1c4d7e8f|cauda equina]], the bundle of nerve roots at the lower end of the spinal canal. This compression leads to a constellation of debilitating symptoms requiring urgent surgical decompression.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Most commonly caused by a massive midline lumbar disc herniation. Other causes include spinal stenosis, tumors, trauma, and epidural abscess or hematoma.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Characterized by a combination of symptoms including <mark>severe low back pain</mark>, radicular pain in one or both legs, and <mark>saddle anesthesia</mark> (loss of sensation in the perineum, buttocks, and inner thighs).</li><li><b>Red Flag Symptoms:</b> The most critical signs are <mark>bowel and/or bladder dysfunction</mark> (e.g., urinary retention or incontinence) and loss of the [[ce2052d6|anal wink reflex]].</li><li><b>Motor/Sensory Deficits:</b> Patients typically have asymmetric, flaccid paralysis or weakness in the lower extremities (LMN signs) and sensory loss.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> <u>Urgent surgical decompression</u> is required to relieve the pressure on the nerve roots and prevent permanent paralysis and incontinence.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The combination of low back pain, saddle anesthesia, and new-onset urinary retention is the classic triad for Cauda Equina Syndrome and warrants immediate surgical consultation.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Cauda Equina Syndrome</b> is a critical condition where compression of the lumbosacral nerve roots leads to a devastating loss of lower extremity and pelvic floor function; its hallmark 'red flag' symptoms of saddle anesthesia and bladder/bowel dysfunction signal the need for immediate surgical intervention to prevent permanent disability.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Massive Lumbar Disc Herniation] --Compresses--> B(Cauda Equina); B --> C(Saddle Anesthesia); B --> D(Bowel/Bladder Dysfunction); B --> E(Lower Extremity Weakness);"
