  "3fa071ef": {
    "title": "Caudate Nucleus",
    "primaryType": "anatomy",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroanatomy",
      "Movement Disorders",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Anatomy and Physiology",
      "Basal Ganglia"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Caudate Nucleus</b> is a C-shaped nucleus that is a key component of the [[ed462927|basal ganglia]]. Together with the putamen, it forms the striatum, which is the main input station for the basal ganglia circuits involved in motor control and cognitive functions.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Anatomy:</b> A large C-shaped structure with a head, body, and tail that follows the curve of the lateral ventricle.</li><li><b>Function:</b> The caudate is primarily involved in the <mark>cognitive</mark> aspects of movement, including motor planning and procedural learning. It also plays a role in reward and motivation.</li><li><b>Striatum:</b> The caudate and putamen are collectively known as the striatum.</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> Atrophy of the caudate nucleus is the hallmark pathological finding in <mark>[[ffd7e743|Huntington disease]]</mark>.</li><li><b>Imaging Finding:</b> The degeneration of the caudate head in Huntington disease leads to the characteristic appearance of <mark>enlarged lateral ventricles</mark> on brain imaging (ex vacuo ventriculomegaly).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The association between caudate atrophy and [[ffd7e743|Huntington disease]] is extremely high-yield. A brain scan showing 'boxcar' ventricles due to a shrunken caudate in a patient with chorea is classic for Huntington's.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Caudate Nucleus</b> is a critical part of the basal ganglia's cognitive loop, and its profound atrophy in [[ffd7e743|Huntington disease]] is directly responsible for both the characteristic motor (chorea) and cognitive (dementia) decline seen in the disorder.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Caudate Nucleus] --Atrophy in Huntington's Disease--> B(Enlarged Lateral Ventricles); A --Part of Striatum--> C(Receives Cortical Input); C --> D(Modulates Motor & Cognitive Function);"
