    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Cavernous Sinus Thrombosis</b> is the formation of a blood clot within the [[c260efc8|cavernous sinus]], a rare but life-threatening condition that is most often caused by a contiguous spread of infection from the face, sinuses, or teeth.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Most commonly a septic thrombosis resulting from infection. The most common pathogen is <mark><i>Staphylococcus aureus</i></mark>. Infection can spread from the 'danger triangle' of the face, sphenoid or ethmoid sinuses, or dental abscesses via the valveless facial venous system.</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> The thrombus obstructs venous drainage and causes inflammation, leading to increased pressure within the sinus and compression of its contents.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Patients present with severe headache, high fever, and signs of [[9a089fd7|cavernous sinus syndrome]]: ophthalmoplegia (CN III, IV, VI palsy), periorbital edema, proptosis, and chemosis. The [[dd11dde6|abducens nerve (CN VI)]] is often affected first.</li><li><b>Diagnosis:</b> MRI with magnetic resonance venography (MRV) is the imaging modality of choice.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> Requires prompt initiation of broad-spectrum IV antibiotics and consideration of anticoagulation.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient with a recent facial furuncle or sinusitis who develops a severe headache, fever, and unilateral eye swelling with impaired eye movements is the classic presentation for cavernous sinus thrombosis.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Cavernous Sinus Thrombosis</b> is a septic clot in the brain's central venous drainage system, typically seeded by a facial infection, which rapidly evolves into a neuro-ophthalmologic emergency with high fever, headache, and paralysis of eye movements.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Facial/Sinus Infection] --Staph. aureus--> B(Spread via Valveless Veins); B --> C(Cavernous Sinus); C --> D(Thrombosis & Inflammation); D --> E(Cavernous Sinus Syndrome);"
