    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Central Post-Stroke Pain Syndrome</b>, also known as thalamic pain syndrome or Dejerine-Roussy syndrome, is a chronic neuropathic pain condition that develops after a [[c5da3c57|stroke]], most classically one affecting the [[afc0a64b|thalamus]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Caused by a stroke (usually ischemic) affecting the somatosensory pathways, particularly the ventroposterolateral (VPL) nucleus of the [[afc0a64b|thalamus]].</li><li><b>Timeline:</b> Pain does not occur immediately after the stroke. There is typically an initial loss of sensation (numbness) in the affected area, with the pain developing weeks to months later.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Characterized by severe, persistent, and often debilitating pain on the side of the body contralateral to the stroke. The pain is often described as burning, aching, or lancinating.</li><li><b>Key Feature:</b> <mark>Allodynia</mark> (pain provoked by a normally non-painful stimulus, like light touch) and <mark>hyperalgesia</mark> (exaggerated pain response to a painful stimulus) are hallmarks of the condition.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> Very difficult to treat. Options include antidepressants (TCAs like [[c6814506|amitriptyline]]), anticonvulsants (e.g., gabapentin, pregabalin), and in refractory cases, deep brain stimulation.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient with a history of a stroke who later develops severe, burning pain and allodynia on the previously numb side of their body is the classic presentation.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Central Post-Stroke Pain Syndrome</b> is a cruel paradox of sensory processing, where a thalamic stroke that initially causes numbness later gives rise to intractable neuropathic pain and allodynia due to maladaptive plasticity in the damaged central sensory pathways.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
