    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Central Retinal Artery Occlusion (CRAO)</b> is an ophthalmologic emergency characterized by the sudden, painless, and profound loss of monocular vision due to obstruction of the central retinal artery, which supplies the inner retina.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Most commonly caused by a thromboembolism. The most frequent source is an atherosclerotic plaque in the <mark>ipsilateral carotid artery</mark>. Other sources include cardiogenic emboli (e.g., from atrial fibrillation) or giant cell arteritis.</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Occlusion of the artery leads to acute ischemia of the inner two-thirds of the retina, causing rapid and irreversible death of ganglion cells and other neurons.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Sudden, painless, severe monocular vision loss.</li><li><b>Fundoscopy:</b> The classic fundoscopic finding is a <mark>pale retina</mark> (due to ischemia and edema) with a <mark>\"cherry-red spot\"</mark> at the fovea. The cherry-red spot represents the intact choroidal circulation (supplied by the posterior ciliary arteries) visible through the thinned, ischemic fovea.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The triad of sudden, painless, profound monocular vision loss and a \"cherry-red spot\" on fundoscopy is pathognomonic for CRAO. It is essentially a stroke of the eye.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Central Retinal Artery Occlusion</b> is an acute ischemic stroke of the retina, where an embolus blocks its main arterial supply, leading to sudden, devastating vision loss and the iconic fundoscopic image of a pale retina with a contrasting 'cherry-red' macula.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Embolus from Carotid/Heart] --> B(Occlusion of Central Retinal Artery); B --> C(Inner Retinal Ischemia); C --> D(Pale Retina); C --> E(Cherry-Red Spot at Fovea); D & E --> F(Sudden, Painless Vision Loss);"
