      "definition": "<p><b>Central Retinal Vein Occlusion (CRVO)</b> is a common retinal vascular disorder characterized by the blockage of the central retinal vein at the optic nerve head, leading to venous stasis, retinal hemorrhage, and edema.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> The primary mechanism is thrombosis of the central retinal vein, often at the lamina cribrosa where the vein is compressed by a sclerotic central retinal artery with which it shares a common adventitial sheath.</li><li><b>Risk Factors:</b> Strongly associated with systemic vascular diseases like <mark>hypertension</mark>, diabetes mellitus, hyperlipidemia, and glaucoma.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Sudden, painless, unilateral blurring or loss of vision. The severity can range from mild to severe.</li><li><b>Fundoscopy:</b> The fundoscopic exam is dramatic and described as a <mark>\"blood and thunder\"</mark> appearance. It shows diffuse, widespread retinal hemorrhages in all four quadrants, venous dilation and tortuosity, cotton-wool spots, and optic disc swelling.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Differentiate from CRAO: CRVO is a venous 'backup' problem, leading to a hemorrhagic appearance ('blood and thunder'), while CRAO is an arterial 'blockage' problem, leading to a pale, ischemic appearance ('cherry-red spot').</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Central Retinal Vein Occlusion</b> is a vascular 'plumbing backup' in the eye, where a thrombus in the central retinal vein causes a dramatic, widespread backup of blood, resulting in the classic 'blood and thunder' hemorrhagic retinopathy and vision loss.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Hypertension/Atherosclerosis] --> B(Compression of Central Retinal Vein); B --> C(Thrombosis); C --> D(Central Retinal Vein Occlusion); D --> E(Venous Stasis & ‚Üë Pressure); E --> F(Diffuse Retinal Hemorrhages & Edema);"
    },
