    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Central vertigo</b> is a sensation of spinning or dizziness that originates from a problem within the central nervous system, specifically the brainstem or cerebellum. It is generally more serious than peripheral vertigo.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Caused by lesions in the brainstem or cerebellum, such as [[c5da3c57|stroke]] (e.g., lateral medullary syndrome), [[45dd6d19|multiple sclerosis]], tumors, or migraines.</li><li><b>Nystagmus:</b> The nystagmus in central vertigo can be in any direction (horizontal, torsional, or <mark>purely vertical/downbeat</mark>). It is often non-fatigable and may change direction with gaze. It is <u>not</u> suppressed by visual fixation.</li><li><b>Associated Symptoms:</b> Often accompanied by other neurological signs that point to a central lesion, such as [[9914d433|diplopia]], dysmetria, [[9767fd6b|ataxia]], dysarthria, or focal weakness/sensory loss.</li><li><b>Onset:</b> The onset can be sudden or gradual, and the vertigo is often constant and less intense than in peripheral causes.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The presence of <mark>purely vertical nystagmus</mark> is a red flag and is highly specific for a central cause of vertigo. Also, look for other 'central' neurological signs (the '5 D's': Dizziness, Diplopia, Dysarthria, Dysphagia, Dysmetria).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Central vertigo</b> is a sign of a CNS lesion, not an inner ear problem. It is distinguished from peripheral vertigo by its associated neurological deficits and a nystagmus that is often vertical and does not suppress with visual fixation, indicating a more ominous underlying cause like a brainstem stroke.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
