  "bad81d37": {
    "title": "Central Transtentorial Herniation",
    "primaryType": "disease",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Neurosurgery",
      "Critical Care",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology and Special Senses",
      "Pathology",
      "Herniation Syndromes"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Central transtentorial herniation</b> is a type of brain herniation where downward displacement of the cerebral hemispheres, basal ganglia, diencephalon, and midbrain occurs through the tentorial notch. It is typically caused by a diffuse increase in intracranial pressure.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Caused by conditions that increase intracranial pressure symmetrically, such as diffuse cerebral edema, hydrocephalus, or midline tumors.</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> The downward pressure causes a sequential caudal displacement of brainstem structures.</li><li><b>Clinical Progression:</b><br>1. <b>Early:</b> Altered level of consciousness, small reactive pupils (diencephalic compression).<br>2. <b>Later:</b> Mid-position, fixed pupils; decorticate then decerebrate posturing (midbrain/pons compression).<br>3. <b>Terminal:</b> Coma, loss of all brainstem reflexes, respiratory arrest (medulla compression).</li><li><b>Duret Hemorrhages:</b> A key pathological finding is the presence of <mark>Duret hemorrhages</mark>, which are secondary brainstem hemorrhages in the pons and midbrain caused by stretching and tearing of perforating arteries during the downward displacement.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> This is a rostrocaudal deterioration. Look for a progressive decline in consciousness accompanied by changes in pupillary response and motor posturing, often culminating in fatal brainstem hemorrhages (Duret hemorrhages).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Central transtentorial herniation</b> is a devastating downward spiral of the brainstem through the tentorial notch, leading to a predictable sequence of neurological decline from altered consciousness to posturing and death, often marked by the characteristic Duret hemorrhages from vascular shearing.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[‚Üë Intracranial Pressure] --> B(Downward Displacement of Diencephalon/Midbrain); B --> C(Compression of Brainstem); C --> D(Rupture of Paramedian Arteries); D --> E(Duret Hemorrhages);"
    },
