      "Neonatal Injuries"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>cephalohematoma</b> is a subperiosteal collection of blood on the scalp of a newborn, caused by the rupture of blood vessels between the skull and the periosteum during birth. It is a common birth trauma, especially with forceps or vacuum-assisted delivery.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Location:</b> The hemorrhage is located <u>deep to the periosteum</u> (subperiosteal).</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> A firm, well-demarcated swelling on the scalp. A key feature is that it <mark>does <u>not</u> cross suture lines</mark>, as the periosteum is firmly attached at the sutures.</li><li><b>Timing:</b> May not be present at birth but develops over the first few hours to days. It resolves slowly over weeks to months.</li><li><b>Complications:</b> The breakdown of the collected red blood cells can lead to <mark>jaundice</mark> (indirect hyperbilirubinemia). Rarely, it may become calcified.</li><li><b>Differentiation:</b> It must be distinguished from a [[a5ec55b5|caput succedaneum]].<br> - <b>Cephalohematoma:</b> Firm, does <u>not</u> cross suture lines, appears hours after birth, resolves slowly.<br> - <b>Caput Succedaneum:</b> Soft, crosses suture lines, present at birth, resolves quickly.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The inability to cross suture lines is the most important feature for distinguishing a cephalohematoma from a caput succedaneum on an exam.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>A <b>cephalohematoma</b> is a subperiosteal bleed confined by cranial suture lines, appearing as a firm scalp swelling in a newborn after a difficult delivery; its key distinguishing feature is its respect for suture boundaries, and its main complication is neonatal jaundice.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
