    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Cerebellar tonsillar herniation</b> is a life-threatening type of brain herniation where the cerebellar tonsils are displaced downward through the foramen magnum, leading to compression of the medulla oblongata.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Caused by a mass or pressure increase in the posterior fossa (e.g., cerebellar tumor, hemorrhage, or edema). It can also be iatrogenically caused by performing a lumbar puncture in the setting of high intracranial pressure.</li><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> The herniating tonsils directly compress the medulla oblongata.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> This is a rapidly fatal event. Compression of the medullary cardiorespiratory centers leads to <mark>bradycardia, respiratory arrest, and death</mark>. Patients may also present with headache, neck stiffness, and loss of consciousness.</li><li><b>Associated Malformation:</b> This type of herniation is the defining feature of [[b96a6a07|Chiari I and II malformations]], although in those congenital conditions, the process is chronic rather than acute.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> The classic scenario is a patient with signs of increased intracranial pressure (headache, papilledema) who undergoes a lumbar puncture and then rapidly deteriorates with respiratory arrest. This highlights the danger of LP in the setting of unevaluated increased ICP.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Cerebellar tonsillar herniation</b> is the most lethal form of brain herniation, as the downward displacement of the cerebellar tonsils through the foramen magnum directly compresses the vital cardiorespiratory centers in the medulla, leading to swift respiratory and cardiac arrest.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[‚Üë Posterior Fossa Pressure] --> B(Cerebellar Tonsils Displace Downward); B --> C(Through Foramen Magnum); C --Compresses--> D(Medulla Oblongata); D --> E(Cardiorespiratory Arrest);"
